<HEADLINE> S.Korean Opposition Leader Elected as Presidential Candidate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Kim Jong-pil, head of South Korea's
second largest opposition party, the United Liberal Democrats
(ULD), was today elected as the party's presidential candidate in
December's presidential election.
</P>
<P>
A total of 2,575 or 82.3 percent of the 3,190 ballots cast at
the party's convention went to Kim Jong-pil while the other
contender won only 554 votes.
</P>
<P>
In his acceptance speech, Kim said that he would do everything
in his power to get elected and revise the basic law in favor of a
parliamentary cabinet system.
</P>
<P>
Kim, a prime minister in the early 1970s, was one of the
so-called "Three Kims", along with the President Kim Young-sam and
Kim Dae-jung, leader of the largest opposition National Congress
for New Politics (NCNP) party.
</P>
<P>
Kim Dae-jung was elected as his party's presidential candidate
on May 19.
</P>
<P>
The two opposition Kims are likely to start consultations soon
to choose a single opposition candidate for the forthcoming
presidential election in mid-December.
</P>
<P>
Incumbent President Kim Young-sam is barred by the constitution
from seeking a second term.
</P>
<P>
Seven contenders from within President Kim's ruling New Korea
Party (NKP), including two former prime ministers, Lee Hoi-chang
and Lee Soo-sung, are currently campaigning to get the NKP's
presidential nomination in late July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
