<HEADLINE> Former Malian President To Be in Bangui for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Bangui, the capital of Central
Africa, is temporarily calm this morning, reports reaching here
said today.
</P>
<P>
About 50 people were reportedly killed yesterday and many
buildings were damaged during the fighting between the government
troops, the African peace-keeping force and the mutineering
soldiers. Thousands of people have been fleeing the capital city.
</P>
<P>
The African peace-keeping force had been trying to drive the
mutineering soldiers from their strongholds in the city and has already
occupied the southwest part of Bangui that is initially under the
control of the mutineers, said the reports.
</P>
<P>
The only area now controlled by mutineers is the east area of
the city.
</P>
<P>
Former Malian President Amadou Toure is returning to Bangui
today to mediate among the belligerents.
</P>
<P>
In January this year, the African peace keepers began its
deployment in Bangui at Amadou Tour's suggestion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
