<HEADLINE> Jordanian PM's UAE Visit Achieves Positive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Prime Minister Abdul
Salam Majali`s three-day official visit to the United Arab
Emirates (UAE) achieved positive results and advanced the
bilateral relations in various fields, said a senior Jordanian
official here today.
</P>
<P>
Minister of State for Information Affairs Samir Mutawe made
the remarks to the press after Majali briefed the Cabinet today
on his UAE visit concluded Monday.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, the prime minister delivered a message from
King Hussein to UAE President Sheikh Zayed Bin Sultan al
Nahyan.
</P>
<P>
"Jordan believes that Arabs now are passing through a
critical stage and facing the prospects of a new regional
order," said Majali during his meeting with the UAE president.
</P>
<P>
"If we are united, we can be partners in shaping up this
regional order but if we are not, a regional order will be
imposed on us and it might not be in our interest," he added.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Jordan signed a 12-million-dollars loan agreement
with the Arab Monetary Fund (AMF). The money will be used to
help the kingdom cover its balance of payments deficit which
resulted from higher prices of imports like basic agricultural
commodities, especially cereals.
</P>
<P>
The loan corresponds to 50 percent of Jordan's total share in
the fund.
</P>
<P>
Also Monday, Central Bank of Jordan (CBJ) Governor Ziyad
Fariz signed two agreements with the Arab Financing Program (AFP),
under which Jordan will be offered credit facilities worth
12.5 million U.S. dollars over a 18-month period to finance the
import of food commodities from Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
The UAE president paid a visit to Jordan in April this year and
held talks with King Hussein.
</P>
<P>
The UAE is one of the Arab countries that severed ties with
Jordan during the Gulf War in 1991, but in recent years, the
bilateral ties have improved since Jordan distanced itself from
Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
