<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO: Integrated Effort Leads to Effective Meningitis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- An integrated effort by
international organizations like UNICEF and WHO has been
successful in helping African countries to respond effectively to
the 1996-97 meningitis epidemics, cutting figures of both cases
and deaths in the previous season, the World Health Organization
(WHO) said in a press release today.
</P>
<P>
The meningitis season runs roughly from November to April.
Following exceptionally severe epidemics of meningitis in 1995-96
in Africa, when 150,000 cases with over 16,000 deaths were
reported, epidemics in the 1996-97 season were also significant,
but cases and deaths were reduced, with 59,461 cases reported as
of June 1, of which 6,055 were fatal.
</P>
<P>
The International Coordinating Group (ICG), set up in January
1997 in charge of meningitis control, began a two-day meeting here
in Geneva on Monday. The ICG is composed of representatives of the
United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF), the International
Federation of the Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies (IFRC),
Medecins Sans Frontieres (MSF), the Association pour L'Aide a la
Medecine Preventive (AMP), the World Health Organization (WHO), as
well as technical partners from WHO Collaborating Centers and
manufacturers of meningitis vaccine and autodestruct syringes.
</P>
<P>
"Thanks to the ICG, no country which urgently needed vaccine
was denied it; we were able to meet all urgent needs," said Dr
Hiroshi Nakajima, WHO Director-General.
</P>
<P>
A shortage of vaccine was anticipated in 1997 as a result of
unusually heavy demand in 1996, WHO said. The ICG is trying to
coordinate the best use of the limited amount (14 million doses)
of vaccine available for the control of epidemic meningitis in
Africa and to advise WHO on the best means of allocating the
vaccine. It was essential to ensure that the meningitis vaccine
was used where it was needed most and that wastage was avoided.
</P>
<P>
A fund of four million U.S. dollars for epidemic preparedness
has been set up. In 1997-98, the fund will both ensure that
countries have immediate access to vaccine when needed and provide
a mechanism for reimbursement so that countries become
self-sufficient in meningitis vaccine procurement.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 16 African countries committed themselves in
November 1996 to a concerted effort to improve meningitis control.
They have developed national plans of action including training of
district health personnel and laboratory technicians, as well as
an estimation of needs of vaccine and other drugs based on
criteria of population at risk, epidemiological patterns of the
disease and the vaccine stock available at country level. 
</P>
</TEXT>
