<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Life Expectancy in EU to Reach 87: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 24 (Xinhua) -- European Union Babies born now
could have a life expectancy as high as 87 for girls and 83 for
boys, it is one scenario painted by population projections on
Tuesday by EU's statistical office Eurostat.
</P>
<P>
This would be a mighty leap from generations born in the
beginning of this century, who lived on average 20 years less,
Eurostat points out.
</P>
<P>
The scenario presupposes continual improvement of medical care
and healthy life-styles.
</P>
<P>
But the Eurostat report also warns that, if positive influence
slow down and are counteracted by negative factors such as smoking
and stress, progress to longer lives might stagnate. Life
expectancies would then be 82 for girls and 76 for boys, it says.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, at present 21 percent of the EU
population is above 60 years old.
</P>
<P>
Longer lives and considerable changes in reproductive
behavior, which is resulting in far fewer babies, could boost
this to as much as 40 percent by 2050, and one third of this
elderly population might be 80, the report estimates.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
