<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Army Chief Assesses Dangers of Syrian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Army Chief of Staff
Amnon Lipkin Shahak warned today that Syria is continuing to
improve its capability of launching a surprise attack against
Israel.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Shahak told the Knesset (Parliament) Foreign
Affairs and Defense Committee that Israeli army is ready to
quell new Palestinian rioting which could escalate in the
Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
The army chief was giving his assessment of the current
tension between Israel and Syria and the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) due to the stalemate in both peace tracks.
</P>
<P>
Shahak said Syrian army has been improving its offensive
capabilities since last September. He noted Syria has redeployed
troops near the strategic Golan Heights between the two
countries, and sharpened its capability of launching a surprise
attack against Israel.
</P>
<P>
He expressed concern that both Syrian army and civilian
officials recently began talking more about war instead of
peace. But he added that Israeli army intelligence did not
detect any intention by Syria to launch a surprise attack in the
near future.
</P>
<P>
The general also noted that Syria recently opened three
border crossings with Iraq, one of arch enemies of Israel, in a
bid to improve relations with Baghdad. He believed that the
Syrian move reflected its anger toward Israel over the prolonged
stalemate in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of south Lebanon where Israel has been bogged
down in a tough guerrilla war with Hezbollah forces, Shahak said
the recent public debate raised by mothers of soldiers serving
in south Lebanon caused damage to the troops.
</P>
<P>
He said while the mothers had the right to call for
unilateral withdrawal from south Lebanon, he thought such a move
would be more dangerous than remaining in the region. He said,
instead of a public debate, a political decision needed to be
made on the issue of south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
On the Israeli-Palestinian violence, Shahak warned that
Israeli troops had been given clear orders on how to quell new
Palestinian rioting. He said the army was doing everything
possible to keep the situation under control in face of the
recent riotings. He foresaw casualties on both sides if a future
violent confrontation erupted.
</P>
<P>
Shahak claimed that the PNA was interested in continuing the
violence at a low level in order to reap political gains, but it
did not want an open confrontation at the stage and acted to
prevent authorized terror attacks against Israel.
</P>
<P>
But at the same time, Shahak added, the Israeli-Palestinian
situation remained tense and the Palestinians, frustrated over
the peace stalemate, were waiting for new developments to start a
new round of violence.
</P>
<P>
According to Israel Radio, Israel's Civil Administration on
the territories has prepared several options for the outbreak of
widespread Palestinian violence.
</P>
<P>
The options included arresting Palestinian officials,
confiscation of their VIP cards, application of economic
sanctions including reimposing closure on the territories, and
even establishment of a new Palestinian leadership, the radio
reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
