<DOCNO> XIE19970625.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique Still Faced With Abject Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Although Mozambique has potential
capacity to feed six times its 16 million population, it is still
faced with abject poverty, a United Nations official said in
Bulawayo, Zimbabwe today.
</P>
<P>
Sigurd Marstein, a Mozambique-based U.N. Development Program
(UNDP) officer, said that of the 80 percent of people in Mozambique
living in rural areas, 60 percent are very poor.
</P>
<P>
He said food security is UNDP's major challenge in Mozambique
which now has relative peace and stability after 20 years of
civil war which destroyed the socio-economic potential of the
country.
</P>
<P>
"We have managed to repatriate 1.7 million refugees from
neighboring countries since 1992, but we are now faced with the
task of feeding them," he said.
</P>
<P>
Marstein said that there is plenty of arable land in Mozambique
which could be used to make agriculture more viable as a starting
point in eradicating starvation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
