<DOCNO> XIE19970625.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Intra-African Trade Low, Says Zimbabwean Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Growth of intra-African trade is
hampered by lack of finance and information on available goods
and services, a Zimbabwean cabinet minister said today.
</P>
<P>
Opening a two-day exhibition running concurrently with the
meeting of shareholders of the Africa Export and Import Bank
(AFREXIM) in Harare, Zimbabwe's Finance Minister Herbert Murerwa
said lack of information had resulted in locally available goods
being sourced from elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
"Frequently, the world market is perceived, given the effects
of colonialism, as the metropolitan center by many of our
exporters and importers," said Murerwa.
</P>
<P>
"Products normally available from neighboring countries are
sought far away even where there are no obvious differences as to
both quality and price," he said.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition mounted by various government agencies and
private sector companies is meant to demonstrate the scope of
activities for which the AFREXIM bank provides financial support.
</P>
<P>
The AFREXIM bank was established in 1993 in Cairo of Egypt, with
the task of facilitating and promoting intra and extra African
trade.
</P>
<P>
The bank operates a number of programs to supplement and
leverage trade finances from inside and out of the continent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
