<HEADLINE> Police Arrests 150 Youths in Quebec Holiday Riots </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Some 150 youths were arrested early
today in cities of Quebec and Montreal when trouble erupted for
the second year running at Quebec's Fete Nationale celebrations.
</P>
<P>
Police fired several cannisters of tear gas into crowds of
young people after some windows were smashed in a popular downtown
square of Quebec city, the provincial capital.
</P>
<P>
Some 100 youths were arrested in a square which was the scene
of rioting last year, reports said today.
</P>
<P>
In Montreal, 48 people were arrested after a 30-minute
vandalism rampage on a downtown street.
</P>
<P>
The riots erupted on the day of Quebec provincialwide
celebrations for the holiday formerly known as St-Jean-Baptist
day.
</P>
<P>
Last year, rioting youths looted stores and smashed windows at
the provincial legislative building.
</P>
<P>
About 80 youths were arrested and at least 500,000 U.S. dollars
damage was caused in Quebec city alone.  
</P>
