<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greco-Cypriot Defense Pact Remains Intact, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- A common defense pact between
Greece and Cyprus remains intact and both governments are
determined to safeguard it, a government spokesman of Cyprus said
here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his daily press briefing, Government Spokesman
Manolis Christofides said that "the pact is the achievement of
the Greek and Cypriot governments and is safeguarded fervently."
</P>
<P>
"It plays a significant role in the fulfillment of our
policies and we will protect it," he added.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman made the remarks in response to press reports in
Greece that the Cypriot government's unilateral decision to waive
overflights by Greek military aircraft challenges the pact.
</P>
<P>
The pact, reached in November 1993 between Cypriot President
Glafcos Clerides and the late Greek Premier Andreas Papandreou,
provides Cyprus with sea, air and land cover from the Greek
military in the event of fresh offensive against the island.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government announced the decision in April to
suspend overflights by Greek military aircraft in order to create
a good climate for the U.N-sponsored direct negotiations between
the two communities of Greek Cypriots and Turkish Cypriots in the
island country.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the decision "is not a moratorium on
flights, but a unilateral and conscious decision which we have
taken."
</P>
<P>
Christofides accused Turkish military aircraft of having
repeatedly violating the Cypriot airspace, saying the entries are
illegal and have violated international law.
</P>
<P>
"We consider the Turkish violations as part of the continuing
crime of the continuing invasion and occupation of part of Cyprus
and we consistently denounce them to the United Nations and other
international bodies," Christofides noted.
</P>
<P>
This Eastern Mediterranean island has been divided since 1974
when Turkish troops invaded and took control of its northern
third in the wake of a pro-Athens coup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
