<HEADLINE> Australia, Germany Support Relief Food </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Australia and Germany
decided to donate 2.9 million US Dollars to the World Food
Program (WFP) in support of relief food distribuion to drought
affected regions in Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The WFP Director in Tanzania, Irene Lacy said in a statement
issued here today that Australia will contribute one million
Australian Dolars (about 0.8 million US Dollars) and Germany has
offered to contribute 2.1 million US Dollars.
</P>
<P>
She said that the funds would be used for the procurement
transportation, distribution and monitoring of 7,000 tons of
maize.
</P>
<P>
The UN body had worked very closely with the government and
donor representatives in the country to ensure that the
assessment of relief needs was conducted in a transparent and
measurable way, she said.
</P>
<P>
While the situation in some regions is reported to have eased,
the WFP official said, those households most seriiously affected
by drought will need assistance to the end of July or in August,
depending on the harvest returns in the regions.
</P>
<P>
Recent reports from the government of Tanzania and FAO
indicated that many of the Central regions in the country may
continue to need support, she added.
</P>
<P>
The WFP official told that the four million US Dollars donated
to WFP for drought relief food by Canada, Ireland, Australia,
Germany and Belgium, will provide food rations to some 200,000
persons for a period of 120 days.  
</P>
</TEXT>
