<HEADLINE> Cypriot Bi-Communal Direct Talks Hold out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The backdrop of the forthcoming
direct negotiations between leaders of the Greek and Turkish
Cypriot communities offers hope for reaching a settlement to the
long-standing Cyprus problem, a government spokesman said here
today.
</P>
<P>
Manolis Christofides told his daily press briefing that "we are
not being dragged into negotiations. We are going to these
negotiations willingly because their overall backdrop opens
windows of hope."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said "we are going to the negotiations with
determination and conviction. The declared support of the
political leadership strengthens our negotiating stance."
</P>
<P>
Christofides noted that the Greek Cypriot side has taken
initiatives to focus international attention on the Cyprus
problem and has been spurring on the issue.
</P>
<P>
The National Council, Cyprus' presidential top advisory body,
met Monday in a bid to forge a common strategy among the island's
political leadership on the direct negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The council decided that political party leaders would
accompany President Glafcos Clerides to New York as advisors.
</P>
<P>
The direct negotiations between Clerides and Turkish Cypriot
leader Rauf Denktash are scheduled between July 9 and 13 near the
largest U.S. city.
</P>
<P>
The talks, under the auspices of U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan, are aimed at hammering out a comprehensive settlement to
the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus issue has remained unresolved since 1974 when the
island was divided after the Turkish troops occupied its
northern third in the wake of a short-lived Greek Cypriot coup
seeking union with Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
