<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Supports Extension of Current OPEC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait would support a
decision on the extension of the current oil production ceiling of
the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC), Kuwaiti
Oil Minister Issa Al-Mazidi said today.
</P>
<P>
He was making the announcement through an interview with
official Kuwait News Agency (Kuna) before leaving for Vienna to
take part in OPEC's Ministerial Council meeting scheduled
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He said "we have no choice but to agree on the extension of the
ceiling if agreed by all member states" because oil prices were
low at present.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait at present produces 2 million bpd of oil in line with a
quota set by OPEC while reserves are estimated at 96.5 billion
barrels or 10 percent of the world's total.
</P>
<P>
OPEC's oil production ceiling is standing at 25.03 million
barrels per day (bpd). But OPEC's 11 members have increased
production by more than 2 million bpd since November last year,
reaching 27.05 million bpd in April this year, according to
Kuwaiti oil sources.
</P>
<P>
Production has increased by nearly eight percent above the
ceiling while prices have declined by 20 percent in the first
quarter of this year, Libya's Oil Minister Abdullah Al-Badri said
in May.
</P>
<P>
An extra 400,000 bpd of output from OPEC might be forthcoming
in the second half of the year.
</P>
<P>
Analysts expect Algeria, Qatar, Nigeria, Venezuela and
Indonesia might all add production capacity this year.
</P>
<P>
The oil prices of the Organization of Arab Petroleum Exporting
Countries (OAPEC) have been continuing in a down trend since the
start of this year because of increase of international supply and
decrease of demand.
</P>
<P>
The prices of OAPEC's basket of seven crudes stood at 18.6
barrels per day in March, dropping by 4.9 dollars per barrels
compared to last December.
</P>
<P>
The Brent Blend crude, the world benchmark grade, was trading
at an averaged 19.39 U.S. dollars per barrel in the past four
months.
</P>
<P>
Al-Mazidi said OPEC's ceiling will be decided according to
reports to be presented by OPEC Secretary General and head of the
committee assigned to follow up prices.
</P>
<P>
The most important agenda at the meeting would be the OPEC
member states' commitment to the production ceiling in order to
preserve international crude oil prices, Al-Mazidi said.
</P>
<P>
The minister expected better prices in the third quarter of
1997 due to the cold weather in some parts of the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970625.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
