<HEADLINE> Minister: British Government to Maintain Existing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The new British Labor
Government will maintain the same policy pursued by its
Conservative predecessor towards Kuwait and promote the existing
relations with it, a senior British official said today.
</P>
<P>
British Foreign Minister of State for Commonwealth and Middle
East Affairs Derek Fatchett made the remark before departure at
the Kuwait International Airport after wrapping up a two-day
official visit to the oil-rich Arab nation.
</P>
<P>
"The change of government in Britain does not mean any change
in British policy towards Kuwait," Fatchett told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He underscored the new Labor Government headed by Tony Blair is
"keen to strengthen and improve our existing relationship and I
believe that my visit here today has been a first step to achieve
this objective."
</P>
<P>
Fatchett, who arrived here Monday after visiting Oman, held
separate talks with Kuwaiti amir Sheikh Jaber Al-Ahmed Al-Sabah
and government officials on ways of promoting bilateral relations
on both political and economic fronts and discussed pending arms
deal with the host.
</P>
<P>
He said during his visit he discussed with Kuwaiti officials
"all aspects of our defense relationship," adding that Britain
"remains ready to help Kuwait build up its own defense
capability."
</P>
<P>
On the question of the pending British-made Sea Skua missile
deal, Fatchett said "A point we have stressed throughout is to
ensure the Kuwaiti ability to defend itself."
</P>
<P>
The British minister stressed that "Kuwait remains a very
important market for Britain and we will do all we can to help
support the work of British exporters."
</P>
<P>
The two countries signed a defense cooperation agreement
following the 1991 Gulf War to end the Iraqi occupation of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
He also said his country would "help maintain pressure on
Iraq to comply with all U.N. Security Council Resolutions."
</P>
<P>
On the Middle East peace process, Fatchett affirmed that
Britain would assist in the peace process to achieve a "political
cooperation, the political freedom and the economic prosperity
that we need in the region."
</P>
<P>
Fatchett's tour is the first visit of its kind by a senior
British official to the Gulf since the Labor Party came to power
in the elections last month.
</P>
<P>
Fatchett, who is on a Gulf tour that has already taken him to
Oman, will also visit the United Arab Emirates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
