<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N. Ireland Unionists Poised to Accept New Peace Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 24 (Xinhua) -- David Trimble, leader of the main
pro-British unionist party in Northern Ireland, said today his
party was prepared to accept new Anglo-Irish proposals to break
the deadlock in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The proposals, to be announced by British Prime Minister Tony
Blair to parliament on Wednesday, is designed to include Sinn
Fein, the political wing of IRA, to join multi-party peace
negotiations on the Northern Ireland. Sinn Fein has so far been
barred from such talks because the IRA refused to call a
ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with Blair in the Downing Street office, Trimble,
leader of the Ulster Unionists, the main Protestant party in the
province, told reporters the plan involved the concept of
"parallel decommissioning" by which the IRA would start to
surrender its weaponry as the talks proceeded.
</P>
<P>
By that offer, Blair is hoping to persuade the IRA to resume
the ceasefire they abandoned in February 1996, committing
themselves to political methods to work towards their goal of a
united Ireland.
</P>
<P>
"I think it's possible that we have the basis of a way forward.
But of course this has got to be agreed with all the other
parties," Blair told reporters in New York while attending the
U.N. environment summit.
</P>
<P>
The Irish Republican Army has launched military campaign over
the past 28 years to end British rule in Northern Ireland.
Northern Ireland's Protestant majority, however, favors to remain
in the United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Trimble said parallel decommissioning was not his party's
"first preference," but they could "go along...provided of course
that that is what actually happened."
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams told Irish radio that he had not
seen the proposals yet. But once he sees the government document,
"Sinn Fein will study very carefully the proposals that they are
putting forward." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970625.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Consumer Confidence Scores New Gain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Consumer confidence of the U.S.
advanced again in June, the New York-base research group
Conference Board reported today.
</P>
<P>
The index of consumer confidence rose to 129.6 in June, nearly
two points higher than in May, the group said. The present
situation index climbed more than 5 points to 157.8, up from 152.6
in May. The expectation index held at 110.7, barely off from 111.4
in May.
</P>
<P>
Consumer confidence increased this month in seven of America's
nine major regions, it reported. Some 36 percent of all consumers
say business conditions are "good", up from about 33 percent in
May. Nearly 36 percent say jobs are plentiful, up from about 35
percent in May.
</P>
<P>
The percentage of consumers expecting business conditions to
improve held at about 19 percent, the same figure as in May.
</P>
<P>
"Latest survey results show consumer confidence continuing to
run at historically-high levels," says Lynn Franco, Associate
Director of the Conference Board's Consumer Research Center.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970625.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudan Denies Involvement in Attempt on Eritrean </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese Minister of State for
Foreign Affairs Mustafa Osman Ismail has denied his government's
implication in the attempted murder of Eritrean President Issayas
Aferwerki.
</P>
<P>
Eritrea has charged that Sudan was behind a plot to
assassinate the Eritrean president.
</P>
<P>
In a statement published here today, the Sudanese minister
said that "Sudan has nothing to do with the matter, these are
mere allegations."
</P>
<P>
He said that by making the allegations, the Eritrean regime
wished to evade the involvement of Eritrean agents in the
sabotage attempts recently uncovered by Sudanese security forces.
</P>
<P>
Media reports have quoted an Eritrean government statement as
saying that a Sudanese officer called Nasreddin Babakr Abul
Khayrat had been arrested while plotting to kill Aferwerki.
</P>
<P>
But Ismail said that no one by that name worked for Sudan's
armed forces or security services.
</P>
<P>
He further asserted that the above-mentioned officer belongs
to the Sudanese opposition, adding that the Sudanese government
will produce further information as soon as it is available.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
