<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK PM Hopes to Focus Job, Crime in Next G-7 Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 24 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
said today he wanted the next G-7 summit to be held in Britain to
concentrate on jobs and crime, not merely "glorified photo calls."
</P>
<P>
Blair, just back from his first summit of the Group of Seven
nations plus Russia in Denver, told Parliament he "wants to return
to the original idea" for the summits.
</P>
<P>
"This was my first G-8 summit and I was struck by how much
better the discussions were when we had time to focus on the key
issues common to all our countries. Next year, I want to take that
further and concentrate on fewer issues in greater depth," he told
parliament.
</P>
<P>
"I want in particular to concentrate on two subjects: the issue
of jobs and employability and the challenge posed by organized
crime," he added.
</P>
<P>
His aides said Blair hoped that the leaders could have at least
half a day away from the prying eyes of the media.
</P>
<P>
"We all face the challenge of how to take advantage of
increasing globalization and provide new job opportunities. In
many countries unemployment, particularly among young people, is
far too high" so the job issue must be underlined at the next
summit, Blair stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
