<HEADLINE> New Quakes Shake U.S. Northwest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Several minor earthquakes,
registering 3.4 to 4.6 on the Richter scale, shook northwestern
United States Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The first tremor, which had a magnitude of 4.2, centered 15
miles (25 kilometers) west-northwest of Omak, Washington. It shook
the area at 7:23 a.m. PDT (14:23 GMT), the U.S. Geological
Survey's National Earthquake Information Center said.
</P>
<P>
Three minutes later, an aftershock, measured 3.4, hit the same
area.
</P>
<P>
Another quake registering 4.6 on the Richter scale was felt a
short time later. It was centered about 50 miles (84 kilometers)
west-northwest of Vancouver, British Columbia.
</P>
<P>
The quakes occurred one day after a quake measuring 4.9 on the
Richter scale rattled much of western Washington. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
