<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cairo Tries to Clean up Air </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The Egyptian capital has launching a
campaign to improve its air quality which has deteriorated into
the world's worst.
</P>
<P>
Early this month the Egyptian Environmental Affairs Agency
embarked on the Cairo Air Improvement Project with the backup of
60 million U.S. dollars of technical assistance and funding from
the U.S. Agency for International Development (USAID), according
to Middle East Times.
</P>
<P>
Air pollution is the highest environmental health risk in the
city, causing 10,000 to 25,000 deaths every year, according to a
1994 USAID study quoted in the latest edition of the English weekly.
</P>
<P>
The two most dangerous culprits are lead and particulate
matter, or soot, in air. USAID estimates that Cairo's children
currently lose an average of 4.25 I.Q. points because of their
exposure to lead.
</P>
<P>
In one step, the Oil Ministry switched to unleaded gas in
Alexandria and Cairo a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
The government also decided to impose tougher limit on the use
of diesel fuel to help reduce floating soot, the cause of
respiratory ailments to thousands of Cairo residents.
</P>
<P>
The city's bus fleet, a major consumer of disel, will be
converted to users of compressed natural gas (CNG), a cheap and
clean alternative, according to the government's plan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the private sector is taking initial steps to
convert cars to natural gas as the country is rich in gas reserves.
</P>
<P>
The project also includes developing a system for vehicle
emissions inspection. It will support inexpensive, private-sector
testing and tune-up stations that will allow the government to
enforce emissions standards.
</P>
<P>
USAID, during their investigation, also found several
unexpected sources of pollution like foundries, the habit of
burning garbage and motor bikes using oil-fuel mixers to improve
their performance.
</P>
<P>
USAID has promised to help both private and public sector
smelters clean up their act.
</P>
<P>
The agency has allocated 7-8 million U.S. dollars of the total
aid figure for new projects designed to address these problems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
