<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eurofighter to Go Ahead, German Finance Minister Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 24 (Xinhua) -- German Finance Minister Theo Waigel
said today the Bonn government will hold on to the Eurofighter
project despite controversies over how to fund the costly
warplanes.
</P>
<P>
"The Eurofighter is indispensable due to reasons of defense
policy," Waigel was quoted by German media as saying on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Eurofighter is a joint project developed by Germany, Britain,
Italy and Spain. Except Germany, the other three nations have
already approved the purchase of the modern jets and are anxiously
waiting for Bonn to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
Germany indicated earlier that it wanted to buy 180 Eurofighter
jets to modernize its air force. However There remain doubts over
how to foot the expected 23 billion German mark (13.6 billion U.S.
dollar) bill due to huge shortfall in the government budget.
</P>
<P>
Waigel has proposed to redirect Germany's state aid for the
Airbus airliner to help fund the Eurofighter. A final decision is
expected to be made on June 11 during the German parliament debate
on the 1998 budget.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
