<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Damascus Declaration FMs Conference to Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LATAKIA, SYRIA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The Foreign Ministers'
Conference of Damascus Declaration Signatories will open here
Wednesday, which will tackle issues concerning the Mideast
peace process and other matters of common concern.
</P>
<P>
Sources close to the conference quoted officials at the
secretariat of the conference as saying that there will be
several important and sensitive issues on the agenda for
discussion.
</P>
<P>
Top on the agenda are the freeze of the Middle East peace
process, the Arab strategy in face of the Israeli policy of
intransigence, and dimensions of the military and security
alliance between Israel and Turkey and its negative consequences
on the regional and Arab security.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the fourth Middle East and North Africa economic
conference, due to be held in Qatar in November, will also be a key
issue for discussion.
</P>
<P>
The Damascus Declaration Signatories, which was formed right
after the 1991 Gulf War, groups the Gulf Cooperation Council
members of the United Arab Emirates, Kuwait, Saudi Arabia, Oman,
Bahrain and Qatar, as well as Egypt and Syria.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that the foreign Ministers of the eight
countries will examine a joint Syrian-Egyptian working paper on
ways and means of establishing an Arab common market to confront
regional and international economic blocs.
</P>
<P>
Syria and Egypt are promoting the Arab common market as an
alternative to a Middle East market through which Israel will be
placed within the Arab economic structure.
</P>
<P>
The sources said Arab countries fear that the introduction of
Israel into Arab economy will ultimately lead to Israeli economic
hegemony over the Arab market in view of Israel's economic and
technological superiority in the region.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the conference will discuss the prospects of an Arab
resolution on the restoration of Iraq to the Arab ranks,
particularly after Syria and Egypt restored economic and trade
relations with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Political observers hold that the Damascus Declaration
foreign ministers conference, embracing the politically,
economically and militarily significant Arab states, constitutes
the beginning of a unified Arab stance, paving the way for an
expanded Arab summit to work out an Arab strategy against the
challenges confronting the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
