<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Major Parties Support PM-Designate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Three major opposition parties of
Turkey today voiced their support for Turkish Prime
Minister-designate Mesut Yilmaz who is trying to form a new
government.
</P>
<P>
Following a meeting with Yilmaz, the Democratic Left Party
(DSP) leader Bulent Ecevit told reporters that his party would
give full support for the new government.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit, also former prime minister, said that all secularist
leaders should back Yilmaz, describing the support for the new
government as "a national duty."
</P>
<P>
Husamettin Cindoruk, whose Democratic Turkey Party (DTP) has
seven seats in the parliament, also declared his support for a
government of Yilmaz, adding he made the decision for the survival
of Turkey's democracy.
</P>
<P>
The Republican People's Party (CHP) leader Deniz Baykal
affirmed that his party would not join the new government, but
all the 49 CHP deputies would be its supporters.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that the support by the DSP, DTP and CHP
meant a great help for Yilmaz's success to win a vote of
confidence in the 550-seat parliament.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz, chairman of the Motherland Party (ANAP), the second
largest political party in Turkey, was appointed by President
Suleyman Demirel to form the next government following the
resignation of Islamist Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan on June
18.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, Yilmaz also met with the True Path Party (DYP)
leader Tansu Ciller, but failed to persuade Ciller to change her
position.
</P>
<P>
Following the meeting, Ciller, also deputy prime minister and
foreign minister of the present caretaker government, told
reporters that she refused to exchange views with Yilmaz over the
government issue.
</P>
<P>
"I did not discuss the government issue so as not to
legitimise Yilmaz's position," she said, adding the ANAP leader
should "return the mandate immediately to the president."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, caretaker Prime Minister Erbakan told his Welfare
Party (RP) members today that Yilmaz should hand over the
mandate to Ciller to set up a new government.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz has started since Monday rounds of thorny talks with
leaders of various parties in an effort to form a new government.
</P>
<P>
He said the new government would be one of what he termed as
cohesion and reconciliation, adding it aimed to solve the
problems of the country within the framework of democracy.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister-designate, however, rejected talks with
the Erbakan-led RP and the Grand Unity Party (BBP) led by Muhsin
Yizicioglu.
</P>
<P>
BBP, which has eight seats in the parliament, vowed to support
a DYP-RP coalition government.
</P>
<P>
For the time being, Yilmaz has enjoyed 265 votes in the
parliament, not enough to survive a possible vote of confidence
in the 550-seat legislature with a vacancy of two.
</P>
<P>
If the new government fails to win a vote of confidence in
the parliament, the mandate to form a government will naturally
go to Ciller, whose DYP ranks the third in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan resigned last week under the pressure from both the
military and his junior coalition partner DYP who criticized the
government's failure in curbing the rapidly-expanding
fundamentalism in the secular republic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
