<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian Court Rejects Ban on Female Circumcision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 24 (Xinhua) -- An Egyptian court today overturned a
ban on performing female circumcision in hospitals, putting an end
to the government's campaign to exterminate a popular ritual in
this largely Islamic country.
</P>
<P>
This ruling will allow the operation to be carried out in all
state and private clinics. But amateurs are banned to do the
delicate job though it is common that midwives and barbers are
entrusted in poor urban and rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Judge Abdul Aziz Hamade said the court overturned the ban
because it was imposed a year ago without parliamentary approval,
rather than making a statement on the nature of the female
circumcision.
</P>
<P>
A group of doctors in Cairo filed a case last September demanding
that the government overturn the ban.
</P>
<P>
Female circumcision, also known as female genital mutilation,
is common in Egypt despite a government ban on health care workers
performing the procedure.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that between 70 and 90 percent of Egyptian
women have undergone the procedure, most of them, girls of 8-12
years old.
</P>
<P>
Many believe it curbs a girl's sexual appetite or enhances
cleanliness. Others say it is required by Islam, although Muslim
scholars disagree over this. Some Egyptian Christians also follow
the practice. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
