<HEADLINE> Picture Exhibition on Hong Kong Opens in Yaounde </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, June 24 (Xinhua) -- A photo exhibition entitled "Hong
Kong -- the Past and Present" was unveiled here today to
commemorate its forthcoming return on July 1 to China.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Ambassador to Cameroun Zhu Yourong presided over the
opening ceremony of the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
Cameroun's Minister of Culture Esaie Mangan, Minister of
Higher Education Peter Tabi, former Foreign Minister Jean Keutcha
and the heads of the diplomatic missions in Yaounde were among
the 100 people present at the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese ambassador said, China will resume the exercise of
sovereignty over Hong Kong on July 1, 1997, adding the event is
of great importance to the Chinese people as well as the people
in the world.
</P>
<P>
Cameroun's Culture Minister Esaie Mangan highly appraised the
concept of "one country, two systems" proposed by the late
Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping, saying China has set a good example
for the the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
British Ambassador to Cameroun Nicolas Mecarthy, who was also
at the ceremony, said his government is very positive about the
future of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Sponsored by the Chinese Ambassy in Cameroun, the exhibition
features some 90 pictures that fully displayed Hong Kong's
history and development.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition will last for one week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
