<HEADLINE> House Approves MFN for China With Healthy Majority </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The House of Representatives
today rejected an attempt to overrule a decision made by President
Bill Clinton to extend the Most Favored Nation (MFN) trade status
for China, and approved of maintaining the normal trade relations
between the United States and China.
</P>
<P>
The result came after Representatives voted 259 to 173 against
Republican Representative Gerald Solomon's bill to overturn
Clinton's decision.
</P>
<P>
Supporters for the normal trade relations between the United
States and China believed revocation of China's MFN could simply
deal damaging blows to the Sino-U.S. relations and affect greatly
U.S. strategic interests in the Asian Pacific region as well as
U.S. economic interests as the Sino-U.S. trade provides a great
amount of opportunities of jobs and cheap consumer goods for
Americans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
