<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Workers' Income Unchanged in 1995 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The median employment income of
Canada's labor force was essentially unchanged in 1995 as
compared to 1994, Statistics Canada reported today.
</P>
<P>
The median, the point at which half the population are above
and half are below, was 20,600 Canadian dollars (14,800 US
dollars) in 1995.
</P>
<P>
This was "24 dollars less than the amount required to keep up
with the increase in the consumer price index," the federal agency
said.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, the median employment was 25,900 dollars (18,600 US
dollars) for men and 16,000 (11,500 US dollars) for women. Both
men and women experienced an increase on a current dollar basis.
</P>
<P>
Yet, "the gains were not sufficient to withstand inflation,"
the agency noted.
</P>
<P>
The number of Canadians who earned income from employment at
any time in 1995 increased by 223,470 to reach 14.4 million, the
largest change since 1989, the agency said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
