<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Jiangsu Province Eyes on US Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 24 (Xinhua) -- East China's Jiangsu Province is
trying to make a rousing performance on the U.S. market after it
has made marked progress in Southeast Asia and Europe.
</P>
<P>
A high ranking economic and trade delegation from the province
started a three-day trade fair today in the World Trade Center,
now the facilities for many of China's trade activities in New
York.
</P>
<P>
Headed by Chen Huanyou, the first senior adviser to the
People's Government of Jiangsu Province, the delegation includes
about 150 officials and business people from 13 cities and a
number national level development zones, trading companies and
about 80 enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Li Daoyu, Chinese ambassador to Washington, made a timely
presentation at the opening ceremony. "Despite the ups and downs,
China-U.S. relations have made positive progress recently," he
said. In 1996, the United States became China's second largest
trading partner, while China was the fourth for the U.S. Up to
now, American investment in China has reached 14.3 billion U.S.
dollars, he said. "The progress is amazing," the Chinese
ambassador added.
</P>
<P>
Li said he hopes that the Jiangsu fair can serve as another
good opportunity to further the efforts for strengthening the
trade and economic cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese delegation has brought along more than 300 projects
for establishing cooperation or joint ventures in Jiangsu, with
each requiring at least a million U.S. dollars. All the projects
offered will cost a total of 6 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Taking the advantages of its ideal geographic location and
convenient transport and telecommunication facilities, Jiangsu has
attracted foreign investment for growingly bigger projects,
according to Chen, who is also secretary of the provincial Chinese
Communist Party committee. By the end of 1996, there had been more
than 2,000 projects with an investment of above 10 million U.S.
dollars each. And 20 of them exceeded 100 million U.S. dollars
each, he said.
</P>
<P>
Jiangsu's trade with the U.S. is also developing rapidly, said
Chen. In 1996, its trade volume with the U.S. rocketed to 3.03
billion U.S. dollars from 657 million U.S. dollars in 1980. Its
products sold to the U.S. market also covered wide ranges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
