<HEADLINE> Australia to Export Missile Decoys </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The Australian government is to
sign a collaborative deal worth 85.5 million U.S. dollars to
supply Australian-developed missile decoys for the United States,
Canada and the Royal Australian Navy.
</P>
<P>
Australian Defense Minister Ian McLachlan said here today,
"It is a major export and it's a major defense industry success
for Australia."
</P>
<P>
The anti-ship missile decoys called Nulka are capable of luring
missiles, such as the French-designed Exocet, away from their
targets, he said. The deal is being signed with the Australian
arm of British engineering group British Aerospace.
</P>
<P>
Nulka, an aboriginal word meaning "be quick", arose from
research conducted by the Australian Defense Science and
Technology Organization (DSTO) in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
The DSTO envisaged a hovering rocket launched from a warship
and simulating its electronic emissions to present a much more
attractive target to missiles.
</P>
<P>
Extensive testing by the Australian and U.S. navies showed it
worked effectively against a wide variety of possible threats.
</P>
<P>
Last August, the government announced a 44-million-dollar deal
to equip Australian warships with Nulkas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970625.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK to Remain International Financial Center: Bankers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The executives of three
influential banks in Hong Kong agree that Hong Kong will continue
to retain its status as an international financial center after
its return to China.
</P>
<P>
Alexander S. K. Au, vice chairman and chief executive of Hang
Seng Bank; Ian R. Wilson, general manager of the Hong Kong, China
Northeast Area of the Standard Chartered Bank; and David Li
Kwok-po, vice chairman and chief executive of the East Asia Bank,
outlined financial prospects of Hong Kong at a forum held here
today.
</P>
<P>
At the end of 1995, Ian R. Wilson said that Hong Kong had 357
foreign-funded banks, ranking second in the world after London.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong ranks 5th in the world in terms of net daily turnover
of the foreign exchange market after Singapore, Japan, US and UK.
</P>
<P>
"At present in Hong Kong we have 182 fully licensed banks, 64
restricted-license banks, 121 deposit taking companies and 157
representative offices making a total of 524 financial
institutions," he said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's financial markets are characterized by a high
degree of liquidity and operate under effective and transparent
regulations, which meet international standards.
</P>
<P>
He said, "We have a big stake in Hong Kong and use Hong Kong as
a regional hub. We feel very much at home in Hong Kong and we have
every confidence in the future of Hong Kong."
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Au said that this is especially true of Hong
Kong in its role as a major international financial center thanks
partly to its ideal location in southern China and at the trade
crossroads of Asia.
</P>
<P>
He said that China has every intention of preserving Hong Kong
as an international financial center after the handover. the Basic
Law of Hong Kong provides specifically for the maintenance of Hong
Kong as an international financial center, he added.
</P>
<P>
China has stated that Hong Kong will continue to formulate its
own monetary and financial policies and pursue a low-tax policy.
The free flow of capital will be safeguarded and the Hong Kong
dollar-US dollar peg will remain.
</P>
<P>
The risk assessment of Hong Kong's post-1997 business
environment by overseas organizations is increasingly positive.
</P>
<P>
"I firmly believe Hong Kong will continue to offer unique value
with its unique qualities, especially as the gateway to China," he
said.
</P>
<P>
David Li said that 25 percent of Hong Kong's economy is related
to financial services which make up eight percent of Hong Kong's
gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
Development of the local economy and opportunities offered by
the inland areas of China have turned Hong Kong into an
international financial center, he noted.
</P>
<P>
All the factors contributing to the success of Hong Kong will
continue to exist after the Special Administrative Region (SAR)
Government is established on July 1. Hong Kong will strengthen its
status as an international financial center with greater support
from the inland areas, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
