<HEADLINE> hkhk - HK's Beautification Lighting Displays Switched On </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The skyline of Hong Kong has
been further lit up since a switching-on ceremony was held here
Wednesday for the city's beautification lighting displays.
</P>
<P>
Urban Council Chairman Leung Ding-bong, officials and
representatives from the sponsors officiated the ceremony held at
the Hong Kong Cultural Center in Tsim Sha Tsui, Kowloon, for the
UC's City Beautification Scheme (CBS).
</P>
<P>
Addressing the ceremony, Leung said the CBS was tied in with
the important historical moment of Hong Kong's return to China.
"It is launched for the public and visitors to enjoy the
magnificent lighting and beautiful landscape."
</P>
<P>
Other than the lighting displays, the Scheme also involves
massive planting work at various sites as part of the UC's
on-going greening program for the urban areas, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Scheme costs a total of 14 million HK dollars (about 1.8
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The CBS includes mounting of the spectacular lighting and
decorative lanterns at such major UC venues on both banks of the
habor as the Hong Kong Cultural Center, Space Museum and the City
Hall.
</P>
<P>
It also includes landscape improvement featuring greenery,
rockery and fountains at various spots, and enhancement of UC
landscapes at about 30 amenity sites in Tsim Sha Tsui, Kowloon
City, Central and Wan Chai.
</P>
<P>
A total of 500 tons of rock features have been used, and more
than 480 trees, 150,000 shrubs and 60,000 flowers planted.
</P>
<P>
The lighting of the Scheme will be on display for more than
three months while the enhanced landscape will be maintained as
permanent features. 
</P>
</TEXT>
