<HEADLINE> Damascus Declaration Foreign Ministers End First </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LATAKIA, Syria, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The first meeting of the
Foreign Ministers of the Damascus Declaration Signatories (DDS)
ended here this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The closed-door meeting lasted four hours after the opening
ceremony that was chaired by Syrian Foreign Minister Farouq
al-Shara in his capacity as foreign minister of the host country.
</P>
<P>
In his opening speech, Shara underscored the importance of
the conference as the Arab nation was facing three challenges,
foremost among which was the one confronting the peace process.
</P>
<P>
He accused Israel of blocking the Middle East peace process,
being engaged in occupation activities and launching repeated
attacks against south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Shara said that the Turkish-Israeli military alliance, which
has alarmed all Arab countries, represents the second challenge.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he said, the commitment of Arab states to the
Arab solidarity needs to be honored.
</P>
<P>
Shara also confirmed that the Arab states had been seeking to
achieve a just and comprehensive peace on the basis of
international legitimate resolutions.
</P>
<P>
He criticized the United States for having participated in the
Turkish-Israeli naval exercises and for ignoring the fact that it
was the co-sponsor of the peace process in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers of the DDS will hold second session this
evening.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian minister revealed that a cordial and fraternal
atmosphere prevailed in the unofficial consultations among the
participating foreign ministers Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
The DDS, which was formed shortly after the 1991 Gulf War in a
bid to increase military cooperation, comprises the Gulf
Cooperation Council members of the United Arab Emirates, Saudi
Arabia, Oman, Kuwait, Qatar and Bahrain, as well as Egypt and
Syria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
