<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Military Official on Russian-Chinese Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Russian Premier Viktor
Chernomyrdin's visit to China scheduled on June 26-28 will promote
the development of military and technical cooperation between the
two countries, the Itar-Tass news agency quoted a high-ranking
official of the General Staff of the Russian Armed Forces as
reporting today.
</P>
<P>
The official, the report does not give his name, said that the
joint declaration signed by Russian and Chinese leaders last year
in Beijing favors trustful and mutually advantageous partnership
aimed at a strategic interaction not only in this century but also
in the 21st centary.
</P>
<P>
He noted that cooperation between Russia and China is not
directed against third countries and is called upon to promote
geostrategic stability in east Asia and ensure lasting peace in
the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
The military relations between the two countries were
developing quite rapidly in 1992-1997, the Russian military
representative was cited.
</P>
<P>
As many as 26 aircraft of the Shukhoi trademark were delivered
to China by the end of 1992, and the volume in the area of
military-technical cooperation between Russia and China reached
1.8 billion dollars, he said.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also discussed China's requirement of Russian
military equipment for the period up to the year 2000, when Zhan
Wannian, the chief of the General Staff of the People's Liberation
Army of China, was on a visit in Russia in August 1993.
</P>
<P>
The Russian and Chinese presidents signed a joint agreement on
non-targeting of strategic nuclear missiles and refraining from
the first uses of nuclear weapons, when Chinese president Jiang
Zemin visited Moscow in July 1994.
</P>
<P>
In April 1996 in Shanghai the heads of five states -- Russia,
China, Kazakhstan, Kirghizia and Tajikistan, signed an agreement
on confidence-building in the military sphere in the border area
-- a first such agreement in the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
A protocol on military and technical cooperation between Russia
and China was signed in Beijing in December 1996. It was agreed
that Russia would sell China a consignment of Russian destroyers
of the latest make, of Sovremenny class, and that armaments and
navigation systems of Chinese naval ships of this type will be
modernized.
</P>
<P>
A Five-Nation Agreement on Mutual Force Reduction in the Border
Area was signed in Moscow by leaders of Russia, China, Kazakhstan,
Kirghizia and Tajikistan on April 24, 1997, when Chinese president
Jiang Zemin was on an official visit in Russia. It was described
by Russian President Boris Yeltsin as a landmark agreement
creating a zone of stability on the border stretch of 7.5 thousand
kilometres, the Itar-Tass said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
