<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Hero of Ocean Exploration Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Jacques Cousteau, known as the
"French Captain" who devoted his life to ocean exploration died
here today at the age of 87.
</P>
<P>
Cousteau, who shot numberous ground-breaking films of the
underwater world, was admired throughout the world and was
described by French President Jacques Chirac "a great Frenchman
and a world citizen".
</P>
<P>
Local media described Cousteau as the "uncontested master of
French oceanography".
</P>
<P>
Beginning his ocean adventures as a corvette captain in 1930s,
Cousteau invented the aqualung for divers.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to shoot oceanographic documentaries during World War
II, he turned a British mine-sweeper into an exploration ship and
shot scientific movies like "World of Silence", "Red Fish", and
"World without Sunshine" which drew millions of viewers worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Cousteau also shot many popular television programs about
ocean stories in the United States, and founded the Cousteau Society
in Norfolk, Virginia.
</P>
<P>
He resigned from the prestigious French Academy in 1995 to
protest against Chirac's decision to resume nuclear tests in the
South Pacific.
</P>
<P>
Cousteau also lobbied the 1992 Rio Earth Summit to save the
Amazon tropical forest and protect the Antarctic. In his later
years he also expressed his concern over the problem of
over-population on the Earth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
