<DOCNO> XIE19970625.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Welcome Party for Journalists Covering HK Handover </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Federation of
Journalists hosted a welcome reception here today for Chinese and
overseas journalists covering the return of Hong Kong to China on
July 1.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest figure from the Handover Ceremony
Coordination Office under the Hong Kong Government, there are now
more than 8,000 journalists from 778 media institutions across the
world in Hong Kong to cover the Hong Kong handover.
</P>
<P>
"July 1 is a historic moment. This is a great opportunity for
us," Chan Tin-ming, chairman of the Hong Kong Federation of
Journalists, told the several hundred journalists attending the
reception in an opening speech.
</P>
<P>
He said that the local media are glad to join journalists from
all over the world to "witness this important historic event."
</P>
<P>
Talking about freedom of the press in Hong Kong, Chan said that
the Chinese government, for the interests of Hong Kong, has
adopted the policies of "one country, two systems," "Hong Kong
People governing Hong Kong," a high degree of autonomy and the
maintenance of Hong Kong's current lifestyle for 50 years.
</P>
<P>
These policies, he said, have been enshrined in the Basic Law
of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region, which explicitly
provides for freedom of speech and of the press. "In other words,
freedom of the press in the future has been guaranteed, and will
be protected by state policies and laws in Hong Kong," he said.
</P>
<P>
His opinion was reinforced by a statement of the federation
released at today's reception.
</P>
<P>
The statement says: "Detailed and specific clauses on the
guarantee of freedoms of speech, of the press and publishing have
been stipulated in the Basic Law, while commitments have also been
made for the SAR Government to continue to abide by the
'International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights' and the
'International Covenant on Economic, Social and Cultural Rights'
in the future."
</P>
<P>
With such arrangements, the statement says, press freedom in
Hong Kong will be "fully and unequivocally" protected by relevant
national policies and Hong Kong law.
</P>
<P>
Chan said Hong Kong's well-developed media and information
industry will continue to develop with technological advances and
the better flow of information.
</P>
<P>
"We Hong Kong journalists have to put in much effort to uphold
and promote professionalism, and to learn the latest technology,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Describing the handover coverage which has attracted thousands
of journalists to Hong Kong as "a very good opportunity to learn
from each other," Chan said that Hong Kong journalists are eager
to enhance exchanges with journalists from China's interior areas
and from the rest of the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
