<HEADLINE> German Police Seek Banker Suspected to Embezzle 50 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The police in the German southern
city of Munich today disclosed that they have begun an
international search for a German banker suspected to have
embezzled over 50 million marks (28 million US dollars), according
to reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The suspect, Peter Dieter Sommer, 57, formerly managing
director of the capital management company GGK, was believed to
have fled to South America. No trace was found of him since he
went to Mexico on vacation in March.
</P>
<P>
Munich police, which have been investigating the GGK company
for two years on suspicions of fraudulent activities, launched the
search for Sommer after gaining evidence from a former business
partner of his, a Greek national named Benedik Symenonidis, who
was arrested a year ago after found having caused about 200
million mark losses to several companies through fraudulent bond
sales.
</P>
<P>
According to the police, Sommer's personal assets, some of them
legally acquired, totaled at least 100 million marks, which
included a mansion in London and other real estate holdings.
</P>
<P>
GGK was founded in the 1950s and for a time a thriving
financial investment business. It went bankrupt in early 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
