<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "One Country, Two Systems" Promotes a Prosperous China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Tadahiro Sekimoto, chairman of the
board of Japanese electronics giant NEC, said here today that the
"one country, two systems" principle, which reflects the wisdom of
the Chinese people, will bring a prosperous China into the next
century.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with Xinhua Tuesday, Sekimoto said it
is of historic significance that Hong Kong, which was forcibly
taken by Britain in the last century, will soon be returned to
China peacefully under the concept of "one country, two systems"
put forward by the late Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong's peaceful handover to China on July 1 deserves
celebration not only in China, but also in Asia and throughout the
world," the NEC chairman said.
</P>
<P>
Introducing two systems in one country is a great pioneering
undertaking which has drawn global attention and will have a
positive impact on the reunification of the mainland and Taiwan,
he said.
</P>
<P>
After July 1, economic ties between the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HK SAR) and the inland areas will get
closer, Sekimoto said.
</P>
<P>
Recalling his meetings with Chinese President Jiang Zemin and
Premier Li Peng during his visit to Beijing in April, Sekimoto
said he was deeply impressed by the determination of the Chinese
leadership to carry out the reform and opening policies.
</P>
<P>
"China has carried out economic reform on the premise of
maintaining social stability and has achieved a great deal in the
past 10 years and more," Sekimoto said.
</P>
<P>
He said China will play a great role as the economic center of
Asia and the world in the next century.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the "one country, two systems" principle, Hong Kong's
economic environment will see no change after its return to China
and will maintain its prosperity and stability, he noted.
</P>
<P>
"Should the Chinese government consistently uphold the 'one
country, two systems' principle and make the best use of Hong Kong
as an international financial and trading center, then the
economies of both the HK SAR and the inland areas will develop
remarkably," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Optimistic about China's economic development after Hong Kong's
handover, Sekimoto said NEC, which started economic cooperation
with China 25 years ago, will further its cooperation with China.
</P>
<P>
Sekimoto, who was elected chairman of the China Committee
affiliated with Japan's largest economic organization Keidanren in
May, said his committee's main task is to promote Japanese
companies' cooperation with their Chinese counterparts.
</P>
<P>
Japanese business circles will actively cooperate with China in
the fields of state-run enterprises' reform, environmental
protection, energy exploitation and infrastructure construction,
he said.
</P>
<P>
They will also support China in its efforts to enter the World
Trade Organization (WTO), Sekimoto added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
