<HEADLINE> Hong Kong's Return Has Positive Effect On Cross-Strait Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 25 (Xinhua) -- At a symposium held by the Taiwan
Studies Society today, experts on the Taiwan question said that
the return of Hong Kong will have a positive influence on
relations across the Taiwan Strait and will improve possibilities
for the reunification of the motherland.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Dianming, vice-president and secretary general of the
society, said that the "one country, two systems" principle not
only will provide an example for resolving the Taiwan issue, but
also have a strong effect on forces advocating "Taiwan
independence."
</P>
<P>
The international community will realize how strongly the
Chinese government feels about the sovereignty issue, he said, and
the return of Hong Kong is certain to become a force for the
peaceful reunification of the two sides of the Taiwan Strait.
</P>
<P>
Huang Jiashu, a professor at People's University in Beijing,
and Wang Hui, an official from the Ministry of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation, analysed the effects of Hong Kong's return
on cross-strait relations, noting that because Hong Kong and
Taiwan maintain close economic ties, the return will certainly
increase development of cross-strait economic and trade relations.
</P>
<P>
The so-called "national reunification program" of the Taiwan
authorities has collapsed of itself, and direct mail, commercial,
and transport links across the strait are expected to increase,
they said.
</P>
<P>
Li Jian, secretary general of the Association for Shipping
Exchanges Across the Taiwan Strait, said the smooth resolution of
the shipping issue between Hong Kong and Taiwan has resulted in
better conditions for direct shipping across the Taiwan Strait.
</P>
<P>
He said he believes that after 1997, cooperation between Hong
Kong and the two sides of the Taiwan Strait will have good
prospects.  
</P>
</TEXT>
