<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-Premier Calls for Better Yellow River Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier Jiang
Chunyun, speaking at a meeting in Beijing today on a Yellow River
Control and Development Program, called for a better job in
harnessing the river.
</P>
<P>
Jiang told those present at the meeting that the Yellow River
is the cradle of Chinese civilization and has a strategically
important role in the modernization drive. In the past 50 years,
he said, there have been outstanding achievements in harnessing
and developing the river. This in turn has made a great
contribution to China's modernization drive, production, and
people's lives.
</P>
<P>
But, he pointed out that control and development efforts have
fallen behind the demands of national economic growth and social
improvements. Severe droughts, wind, sand, and soil erosion along
the middle and upper reaches, in addition to silting, bursting
dykes, and a lack of water sources along the lower reaches have
all come together to pose great threats to local economic
development and people's lives, he added.
</P>
<P>
A special effort must be made, Jiang noted, to preserve water
and soil, restore vegetation, and improve the eco-system along the
middle and upper reaches, and to reinforce dykes and dams, dredge
waterways, and increase flood-relief measures along the lower
reaches.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the work to bring the river under control must
be done in accordance with natural and economic laws. 
</P>
</TEXT>
