<HEADLINE> Details on Cypriot Bi-Communal Direct Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations has prepared a
document on Cyprus issue to be presented at the Cypriot
bi-communal direct talks next month.
</P>
<P>
The document will be presented by the U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan's Special Representative for Cyprus, Diego Cordovez, to
Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash at the U.N.-sponsored direct talks.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed here today by government spokesman, Manolis
Christofides, who announced some details about the program of the
talks, to take place between July 9 and 13.
</P>
<P>
Christofides told reporters after a cabinet meeting today that
the talks will be held at Troutbeck, Dutchess County, near Amenia
town, north of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
On July 8, U.N. Secretary-General Annan will host a dinner for
Clerides and Denktash, and the representatives of the three
guarantor powers namely Britain, Greece and Turkey, and the
special representatives for Cyprus of Canada, the U.S., Finland,
Germany, Russia and Sweden.
</P>
<P>
Also participating will be China and France and the
representatives of the presidency of the European Union and the
European Commission. Italy and Norway will also be invited to send
a representative to the dinner, according to the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The talks will open with a special ceremony on July 9 with a
statement by the U.N. Chief Annan in the presence of all those who
attended the dinner on the eve of the talks.
</P>
<P>
In the afternoon, there will be a meeting between Clerides and
Denktash at which Cordovez will present the leaders of the Greek
and Turkish Cypriot communities with a U.N. document, the
contents of which was not revealed yet.
</P>
<P>
The program for the remaining days, Christofides said, will be
decided on site.
</P>
<P>
Access to the site of the talks will be restricted but
President Clerides and Denktash will be able to consult their
advisors and confer with them outside the location where the
talks will take place, the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
The forthcoming U.N.-sponsored Cypriot bi-communal talks are
aimed at hammering out a comprehensive solution to the Cyprus
problem, which has remained unresolved since 1974 when the island
was divided after the Turkish troops occupied its northern third
in the wake of a pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
Clerides and Denktash had two informal meetings in Nicosia
under the U.N. auspices, in October 1994, which ended in a
deadlock. They have not met ever since. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
