<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Regulations on Chinese Citizens Travelling Abroad (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Overseas travel is the natural outgrowth of China's reforms and
opening-up, and an indication of the improving standard of living
and cultural interest, and an index of the country's political
stability, economic prosperity, and social development, He noted.
</P>
<P>
China, however, is a developing country, with a low per capita
gross national product, and more than 50 million people living
below the poverty line, he noted.
</P>
<P>
In order to prevent a drain on foreign currency, and to give
priority to national interests, the overseas travel business
should be developed in a controled way, he said.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1990s, there has been a growing demand by Chinese
citizens to travel abroad even though number of travelers,
compared with the total population, is still quite small, the
total number is already large.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the number of Chinese going abroad was more than five
million, making China one of the top sources of tourists in Asia,
and the number of tourists, including those going to Hong Kong and
Macao, was 1.64 million.
</P>
<P>
Although this number is not very large, it is growing quite
rapidly, he said, noting that the new regulations are significant
for establishing a basic system for travel abroad by Chinese
citizens, for providing proper management, and for protecting
national interests and the interests of tourists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
