<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Largest Park in North Hong Kong Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The largest park managed by the
Regional Council, the Tai Po Waterfront Park, opened here today,
adding another ideal venue for the public to spend their leisure
time.
</P>
<P>
The park is bounded by the Tolo Harbor on the south and east
and covering an area of 22 hectares, blends with the spectacular
view of the Tolo Harbor.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony today, Daniel Lam Wai-keung,
chairman of Regional Council, said that plans had been set out by
the Regional Council to provide more recreational, sports and
cultural facilities for members of the public in various
districts.
</P>
<P>
Major new facilities, such as the second phase of Tin Shui Wai
Park in Yuen Long, Po Hong Park in Tseung Kwan O; Tsuen Wan West
Indoor Recreation Center and the second phase of a park in Shing
Mun Valley, Tsuen Wan, have been opened recently.
</P>
<P>
More facilities will be coming on steam in the latter half of
this year, including a 5,000-seat sports ground in Shing Mun
Valley, Tsuen Wan King Circuit Indoor Recreation Center and Ma On
Shan Swimming Pool Complex, he added.
</P>
<P>
The most outstanding feature of the Tai Po Waterfront Park is
that it perches on a hill and from the central highest point,
visitors can capture the view of the whole park and they can also
go up to the 32.4-meter-high lookout tower to have a panoramic
view of the Tolo Harbor and the surroundings.
</P>
<P>
Other features of the park include a 1,000-meter-long
promenade; an insect house with specimens and exhibits on insect
ecology, a western style mazed garden, an ecological garden, a
600-seat amphitheater, a 660-seat sheltered viewing terrace, three
theme children's playgrounds, two bowling greens and a gateball
court. 
</P>
</TEXT>
