<HEADLINE> German Budget Deficit Hits New Record, Claims Opposition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Germany's budget deficit hit a new
record of 53.4 billion marks (31 billion U.S. dollars) by the end
of May, Bonn's main opposition Social Democratic Party (SPD)
claimed here today.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, SPD parliamentary leader Rudolf Scharping confirmed
today that his party would file a lawsuit against the government's
1996 budgetary policy at the country's highest court, the Federal
Constitutional Court.
</P>
<P>
The SPD claims the government has violated the constitution by
running up a new debt higher than the total investment in the 1996
budget.
</P>
<P>
Germany had 78.3 billion marks (45.5 billion dollars) in new
debt in 1996, higher than the total investment of 61 billion marks
(35.5 billion dollars)
</P>
<P>
The new development dramatized Germany's financial plight which
has already put a heavy strain on Bonn's attempt to meet the
budgetary and fiscal requirements for joining the planned single
European currency, the Euro.
</P>
<P>
SPD budget expert Karl Diller said government budget deficit in
the first five months of 1997 had already exceeded the total
new debt approved for the whole year -- 53.3 billion marks.
</P>
<P>
The SPD estimates the government will face a total budget
shortfall of about 30 billion marks (17.4 billion dollars) in 1997.
</P>
<P>
To plug the huge budget hole, Bonn is planning to sell state
assets including its holdings in telecoms giant, Deutsche
Telecom.
</P>
<P>
The German government has also announced that it will submit a
supplementary budget to parliament asking for a higher level of
new debt for 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
