<HEADLINE> Heroin Burned before Sculpture of Hero Against Opium Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Authorities in Fuzhou, capital of
southeast China's Fujian Province, today burned heroin and "ice"
drug before the sculpture of Lin Zexu, China's national hero who
burned opium confiscated from British traders some 155 years ago,
eye-witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
Sources said that some 21 kg of heroin and 210 kg of "ice" were
destroyed this afternoon as part of the anti-drug campaign
launched in the city.
</P>
<P>
Fuzhou is the hometown of Lin.
</P>
<P>
In Yili of Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region where Lin was
exiled after the Opium War, a museum was opened on Tuesday in
memory of his courage against the opium trade and deeds for
reclamation of ethnic region.  
</P>
