<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Meets Visiting Japanese Finance Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng, in a
meeting here today with Japan's Finance Minister Hiroshi
Mitsuzuka, said that this year is the 25th anniversary of the
normalization of Sino-Japanese relations, and that it is an event
worth commemorating.
</P>
<P>
China and Japan have reached an agreement on the exchange of
visits between prime ministers this year, he said, and hopes that
such visits will further the healthy and steady development of
bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Li said that there are good cooperative relations between the
finance ministries of the two countries. Since the scale of
China's modernization is very big, it is one of the country's
long-term policies to attract overseas capital, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Sino-Japanese cooperation in capital is generally good, Li
said, adding that various loans provided by the Japanese side have
been beneficial to the development of China's economic
construction and projects launched with Japanese loans have
produced good economic returns.
</P>
<P>
Mitsuzuka said he was entrusted by Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto to express congratulations on China's resuming exercise
of sovereignty over Hong Kong. he told Li that Prime Minister
Hashimoto is looking forward to the visit to China in the near
future.
</P>
<P>
Mitsuzuka said that the Japanese side is willing to continue
efforts to strengthen cooperation and exchanges with China in the
field of finances, especially in the arrangement and use of
Japanese loans.
</P>
<P>
Mitsuzuka also briefed Li on the recent summit meeting of the
eight in Denver, and said the Japanese government will continue to
push for China's entry into the World Trade Organization. 
</P>
