<HEADLINE> Interview: Jardine Matheson Shows Confidence in HK Future (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua this week, Chairman of Jardine
Matheson (China) Ltd. Martin G. Barrow said: "We continue to have
confidence in Hong Kong as an international business center and we
will continue to invest here."
</P>
<P>
He said Jardine Group is the largest business employer in Hong
Kong, with a staff of some 60,000 working in the city.
</P>
<P>
"Almost 99 percent of our staff are the Chinese among the Hong
Kong residents. I think our staff are very positive about the
future prospects of Hong Kong," he said, adding that the company
has asked the staff from overseas to learn Putonghua (or standard
Chinese) so that they will be ale to better adapt to Hong Kong as
a Special Administrative Region (SAR) of China.
</P>
<P>
"When we give them a letter of appointment, it says that they
must learn the Chinese (language)," he said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Jardine Matheson Group has a very long-standing
involvement in Hong Kong and the interior area and is still very
much committed to development of its business in Hong Kong and
China's interior area.
</P>
<P>
Jardine has been active since the start of China's opening-up
policy in the late 1970s. It first invested in one of the
country's first foreign-funded enterprise in China in 1980 --
Beijing Air Catering Co. at Beijing Airport, and also in one of
the first industrial joint ventures, namely, Schindler Elevator
works both in Beijing and Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
"We are very pleased to participate in the very first
ventures," he said. "Since then we have entered into many business
fields in China, meanwhile we continue to increase our business in
Hong Kong itself."
</P>
<P>
So far, Jardine has a presence in some 30 cities across China
from the northeastern city of Dalian to Haikou in central China,
representing a very broad range of activities. With China's
opening up of the service sector, particularly over the last five
years, Jardine has expanded its business area largely in the
interior area.
</P>
<P>
"We made many new investments in Hong Kong and China's interior
in the last few years," he said. "We have continued to buy other
companies in Hong Kong, we continue to make new investment here in
infrastructure, such as the transportation field, the new airport,
container operations, high technology and the property market. We
also have hotels and merchant banking in Hong Kong."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
