<HEADLINE> Iranian Official Sentenced to 30 Years for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 25 (Xinhua) -- An Iranian government official was
sentenced to 30 years in prison and fined 3.76 million
U.S. dollars for embezzling money allocated for the reconstruction
of quake stricken areas.
</P>
<P>
The Persian daily Iran reported today that Mohammadi Ali
Behmanesh was charged with embezzling money from the funds
allocated by the Housing Ministry for the reconstruction of
quake-stricken areas in northern province of Gilan and
northwestern province of Zanjan.
</P>
<P>
The two provinces were hit by a 7.3-degree earthquake which
claimed 40,000 lives on June 21, 1990.
</P>
<P>
The daily added that Behmanesh was the head of a 12 people
network who all received kickbacks from foreign firms that were
supposed to rebuild the destroyed areas.
</P>
<P>
However, the report revealed neither the background of the
official nor the name of the foreign companies.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the Iranian government had allocated some
250 million dollars for the reconstruction of the quake-stricken
areas. 
</P>
