<DOCNO> XIE19970625.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Tourism Industry Ushers in New Era </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Every tourist to Hong Kong on
July 1 or after will receive a certificate from the Hong Kong
Tourist Association (HKTA), which certifies that he or she
"visited Hong Kong in 1997 and witnessed the historic moment of
Hong Kong's transfer of power."
</P>
<P>
"The return of Hong Kong to China is a grand historical event
that will bring the world's attention to Hong Kong to an
unprecedented height," Kent Hayden Sadler,
deputy-executive-director of the HKTA, said.
</P>
<P>
The HKTA is hoping to seize the opportunity, attract more
tourists to Hong Kong and help the local tourism industry scale a
new height, he said.
</P>
<P>
At present, tourism is the most lucrative sector in Hong Kong
in terms of foreign exchange earnings. In 1996, the Hong Kong
tourism industry earned a record 104.8 billion HK dollars from a
record 11.47 million tourists.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that because of the handover factor, these two
records are likely to be broken this year.
</P>
<P>
The HKTA recently announced that in the 100 days between July 1
and October 8 this year, it would stage a major tourism-promotion
event "100 Wonders of Hong Kong", which would give tourists from
all over the world a chance to visit Hong Kong immediately after
the handover and witness history together with local residents.
</P>
<P>
During that period, visitors to Hong Kong will be able to
participate in a number of special activities and programs, while
enjoying a series of preferential treatment.
</P>
<P>
"This is only one of the measures Hong Kong will take to
develop its tourism industry beyond 1997," said Sadler.
</P>
<P>
Other measures of the HKTA will include organizing a series of
grand events between 1997 and 2001, setting up a representative
office in Beijing, and cooperating with the tourism sector in
China's interior areas in carrying out tourism promotions
overseas, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We will also encourage investment in developing theme parks,
movie cities, and water sports centers in Hong Kong," he added.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that in the next five years, the number of
visitors to Hong Kong will increase at an annual rate of more than
five percent, and will reach 18 million by the year 2005.
</P>
<P>
"A new era will begin for the tourism industry of Hong Kong,"
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970625.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Strong Earthquake Rocks Western Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 25 (Xinhua) -- A strong earthquake registered 5.9
on the Richter scale jolted Shimane Prefecture and a wide area of
Western Japan this evening, the Meteorological Agency said.
</P>
<P>
There were no immediate reports of damage or injuries.
</P>
<P>
The quake occurred at 6:50 p.m.. The epicentral area was about
20 kilometers underground in northern Yamaguchi Prefecture, which
neighbors Shimane Prefecture, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
The agency said two aftershocks of the quake shook western
Shimane Prefecture at 6:58 and 7:06 p.m..
</P>
<P>
The tremor temporarily halted operations between Ogori and Shin
Lwakuni on the Sanyo Shinkansen bullet train line linking Osaka
and Fukuoka, railway operators said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
