<DOCNO> XIE19970625.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zanzibar Foreign Trade in Huge Gap </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 25 (Xinhua) -- A vast trade gap was
experienced in the last four years between Zanzibar and its
principal trading partners, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The trade gap widened by 207 percent in favour of the latter
between 1993 and 1996, an official of the Zanzibar statistical
Bureau told reporters in the town of Zanzibar recently. The
official said the trade gap brought the deficit to widen from
16,498.7 million Tanzania Shillings (about 27.49 million US
Dollars) to 49,734.58 million T.Shs. (about 82.89 million US
Dollars).
</P>
<P>
According to the bureau's statistics, about 10,150.59 million
T.Shs. (about 16.9 million US Dollas) was earned in exports as
commpared to 152,725 million T.Shs. (about 254.5 million US
Dollars) used in imports by the Isles during the period, with
imports of industrial commodities taking the lion's share of
total import expenditure.
</P>
<P>
Imports of industrial commodities went up to 65,679.25 million
T.Shs. (about 109.5 million US Dollars). Equipment for
transportation, medicine, machinery and electricity, as well as
foods and drinks also used large amounts of money. Just a small
portion of import expenditure was allocated for imports of raw
materials, animals and vegetable oils, and in importing petroleum
oil.
</P>
<P>
Zanzibar has used more money in imports of consumer goods as
compared to inputs during the period, it was indicated. No
exports of industrial goods were made during the period despite
adopting export processing campaigns since the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
The statistics showed that traditional products have remained
the only source of foreign currencies.
</P>
<P>
Cloves have remained the major export commoditity, but money
realised from exports declined from 1,257.01 million T.Shs.
(about 2.09 million US Dollars) in 1992 to 883.90 million T.Shs.
(about 1.47 million US Dollars) last year.
</P>
<P>
Since 1991, cloves have been fetching about 50 percent of foreign
currency earnings, followed by sea weeds. Its export increased by
more than 50 percent during the period.
</P>
<P>
Copra, clove oil, centipede, makonyo oil and few other
traditional crops have remained a major contributor in exports,
the statistics showed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
