<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 12:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: T-shirts Add Emotional Touch to HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALEXANDRIA, EGYPT, June 25 (Xinhua) -- With Hong Kong's
handover only 120 hours away, Roger Y.K. Ngan, a Hong Kong Chinese
doing business in the Egyptian port city of Alexandria, found
himself having much to hope for, and of course, much to
commemorate.
</P>
<P>
"All in all, I must do something for my motherland," said Ngan,
who decided to contribute 100 pieces of specially-designed
T-shirts to the gala of July 1 when the handover takes place.
</P>
<P>
"As all the Chinese living in the city dance out the last hours
of over 150 years of colonial rule by the British over Hong Kong
at the midnight party on June 30," Ngan said, "each of us will
sport this commemorative sweater."
</P>
<P>
To him, as well as many Chinese, the white garment, with "97"
and the emblem of the HK Special Administrative Region stitched in
red and green silk thread, is more than merely another show of
business savvy.
</P>
<P>
"I hope this could be an appropriate expression of my gratitude
and happiness," he said, while making a final check of a sample
that just rolled off the sewing machine.
</P>
<P>
Ngan, a 48-year-old Hong Kong Chinese, is a self-made success
in the ultra-competitive ready-wear empire. His 30 years of
acumen earned him bountiful shares in many projects worldwide.
</P>
<P>
His latest investment is a multi-million dollar HK-Egyptian
textile firm inside Alexandria's free trade zone. A producer of
modest casual wears, trousers and pyjamas, the eight-month-old
factory has already set an eye on the European and U.S. markets.
</P>
<P>
Ngan will distribute the smart T-shirts to the invitees to the
banquet to be held in the Chinese General Consulate in Alexandria
marking China's resumption of the exercise of sovereignty over
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"When that historic moment arrives, there should be no regret,
no anxiety but only hope for a better future," the placid and mild
Hong Kong native got rather emotional when talking of the future
of his birthplace.
</P>
<P>
"I expect life and business as usual. Nothing much to change.
Of course, except changes for the better. I am very optimistic
what is good will be carried on into the new era."
</P>
<P>
"People should have nothing to worry about. All the indicators
show business is strong," he added.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the handover would bring an immediate benefit to his
eight-month-old, 2,000-square-meter factory that still experiences
teething pains, according to the board director of the HK-based
Great Eastern Textiles Co..
</P>
<P>
With Hong Kong's return to China, cotton, textile materials and
machines needed by his workshop will be more convenient to be
shipped from China's inner areas at lower costs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
