<HEADLINE> Feature: T-shirts Add Emotional Touch on HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALEXANDRIA, EGYPT, June 25 (Xinhua) --
</P>
<P>
"By then we can expect a big improvement," said Ngan, who
supervises the 310-strong, export-oriented joint venture.
</P>
<P>
Since 1987, Ngan has been shuttling between the Mideast, Hong
Kong and other southern Chinese regions that interest him. In his
opinion, the gap between Hong Kong and the rest of China,
especially the more affluent southern provinces, is simply
omissible now.
</P>
<P>
Four years ago, the Great Eastern Textiles set up a garment
factory jointly with the Chinese Triumph Group in the eastern
province of Jiangsu.
</P>
<P>
"The disparity between Hong Kong and its neighboring areas is
diminishing thanks to ever-expanding cooperation and rapid
development of those regions," said Ngan, reflecting on his
transactions with his business partners there.
</P>
<P>
In a more festive mood, his 11 Chinese office employees are
working against time to rehearse for their choral presentation at
the midnight jubilee on June 30.
</P>
<P>
Highlighting the jubilation over the much-anticipated British
departure, private parties, official celebrations are being held
in Alexandria and Cairo, the Egyptian capital.
</P>
<P>
The energetic Ngan plans a family party in his Hong Kong
residence on July 2. In order to be at home on time, he will have
to catch the earliest flight after leaving the midnight party in
Alexandria.
</P>
<P>
But for Ma Shiyuan, a permanent resident of Cairo, celebrations
will be a pure family affair.
</P>
<P>
"My whole family on that night will be right in front of the
TV for the live coverage of the handover ceremony and the sworn-in
of the new administration," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I am overjoyed that the days of indignity are bygones with the
departure of the British," said Ma, the ethnic Chinese
sexagenarian, who has established himself in Egypt since leaving
his hometown 40 years ago.
</P>
<P>
But the excitement over the highly-publicized event is not
confined to the overseas Chinese.
</P>
<P>
Mohab F. Akhnoukh, managing director of the Great Eastern
Textiles, has booked an expensive trip to Hong Kong on June
29-July 6 to be an eyewitness to the grand event.
</P>
<P>
Even if he risks a rip-off as the cost of the eight-day stay in
a comfortable hotel has rocketed to 23,000 HK dollars.
</P>
<P>
"I'd love to see Hong Kong at the moment when history and
future shake hands," said Akhnoukh, a well-groomed Egyptian in his
early 30s, fresh from an eight-year higher education in Washington.
</P>
<P>
"It's a big occasion for my Chinese colleagues and so a very
important one for me. I've got a lot to learn from them," he
added.
</P>
<P>
It will be Akhnoukh's first trip to China since he took over
family business from his father who has interests in Great
Eastern's operations in China. 
</P>
