<DOCNO> XIE19970625.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa's Trade Falls, Afrexim Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Africa's internal and external
trade recorded a decline last year due to weaker external demand
and high tariff and non-tariff barriers, a banker said on Tuesday
in Harare.
</P>
<P>
Africa export and import (AFREXIM) bank president Christopher
Edordu said the total African trade fell by about two percent to
235 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
He said that intra-African trade declined by five percent to
20.7 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The fall in exports has been attributed to low demand and
reduced commodity prices.
</P>
<P>
"Imports fell significantly as a result of protective measures
in the form of higher tariff and non-tariff barries which stood
at an average of over 27 percent," said Edordu.
</P>
<P>
He said the tariff level in Africa was higher than recorded in
industrial countries as well as in newly industrialising
countries of south-east Asia.
</P>
<P>
He said the decline in African trade could have been worse had
it not been for significant increases in export volumes which
moderated the effect of lower commodity prices.
</P>
<P>
The year also saw Africa's trade as a proportion of global
trade decline to 2.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, Edordu said despite the weak export and trade
institutions which characterised the environment last year,
overall economic conditions were relatively favourable. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
