<DOCNO> XIE19970625.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua Interview With Russian Ambassador To China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Russia's Ambassador to China Igor
Rogachev, who was interviewed by Xinhua, said that the frequent
exchange of visits by Russian and Chinese leaders in recent years
have increased the mutual trust and understanding and that
relations are moving smoothly towards the goal of establishing a
strategic partnership oriented to the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Russia's Prime Minister Chernomyrdin will start his China visit
on June 26 and Russia and China will sign the 1997-2000 trade
agreement and nearly 10 other agreements and memoranda to
strengthen bilateral cooperation in energy and transportation
during that visit, Rogachev said.
</P>
<P>
Russia and China have signed about 150 collaboration
agreements, he noted, and the healthy development of
Russian-Chinese ties is one that has seldom been seen between big
powers in today's world. The border agreement signed by Russia,
China and three other Central-Asian countries last year was also
an example for resolving border issues around the world, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Russian-Chinese economic and trade ties are improving too,
Rogachev continued, saying that bilateral trade volume last year
was 25 percent more than the previous year. The two sides have
used more modern trade methods instead of the traditional barter
trade, he said, and Russia will continue to push for collaboration
between major companies.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador said that cultural exchanges between Russia and
China have also increased and that many artists and musicians have
visited each other since last year and Russia is planning to hold
a China art festival in Moscow this fall so that the Russian
people can get to understand China better. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
