<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia to Produce Low Earth Orbit Satellite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The construction of an Australian
low earth orbit satellite is expected to start before the end of
this year, Australian Science and Technology Minister Peter
McGauran said here today.
</P>
<P>
The 400 kg ARIES-1 (Australian Resource Information and
Environment Satellite) is planned for launch in 2000 and will be
the world's first commercially sustainable resources information
satellite, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Australia's most ambitious space project has moved a step
closer to reality with the completion of a 900,000 US dollar
feasibility study on the satellite, McGauran said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The study, jointly sponsored by the Australian government and a
high profile consortium of local and international industry
groups, confirmed the commercial and technical feasibility of the
satellite.
</P>
<P>
"It will dramatically improve on the existing capabilities for
geological mapping, environmental monitoring and land use
assessment for agriculture, forestry and defense applications
world-wide," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The satellite will monitor the globe on a regular basis to
assess the extent and condition of crops and forests and to map
land degradation, such as overgrazing and salinity.
</P>
<P>
"It will be capable of differentiating between various minerals
in rocks and soils, even through moderate vegetation cover. In
addition, it will be able to detect various vegetation species and
a range of environment indicators," the minister said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970625.0121 </DOCNO>
