<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bus Only Lane in Beijing Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 25 (Xinhua) -- A special lane for buses on one of
Beijing's busiest streets, Chang'an Avenue, opened today as the
first in the Chinese capital, in a move to solve the city's
traffic problems.
</P>
<P>
The special lane is the far right-hand lane and is marked with
a double broken-yellow line. Only buses and mini-buses approved by
the police can use the lane. Traffic authorities say the lane will
help increase buses' speed and encourage more people to ride them.
</P>
<P>
Beijing's roads can not keep up with the increasing number of
motor vehicles. In 1993, there were 27 areas in the city that were
frequently jammed, but now there are 99, and every day, there are
more than 50 traffic jams just on the main streets.
</P>
<P>
Chang'an Avenue running east-to-west across the heart of
Beijing is a major street for public transportation. There are
more than 1,000 buses and some 150 mini-buses traveling on it
daily, moving more than 340,000 people.
</P>
<P>
"Now it takes only 50 minutes to drive the whole route," said a
conductor of a No.1 bus on the avenue. Previously, however, the
bus needed more than an hour, or even two during traffic jams.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
