<DOCNO> XIE19970625.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Damascus Declaration FMs Meeting Opens in Syria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAKAKIA, SYRIA, June 25 (Xinhua) -- A meeting of foreign
ministers of the Damascus Declaration states opened here this
morning.
</P>
<P>
Informed sources here said that the foreign ministers will
discuss issues including the deadlocked Middle East peace process,
the Arab strategy towards Israel's intransigence in executing
U.N. Security Council resolutions, Israeli-Turkish military and
security alliance and its negative effects on both Arab security
and regional security.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers will also study a working paper on
setting up an Arab economic community, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The so-called Damascus declaration was signed in March 1991
among Egypt, Syria and six GCC countries, Saudi Arabia, Kuwait,
Oman, Bahrain, Qatar and the United Arab Emirates in the aftermath
of Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
According to the original document, Egypt and Syria were to
provide up to 100,000 troops to be based in the Gulf to safeguard
the oil-rich states from future threats. In exchange, the Gulf
states were to earmark up to 15 billion U.S. dollars for
development projects in the two countries.
</P>
<P>
But the military pact faltered quickly under opposition from
Iran and Turkey. And since then Kuwait, Bahrain and Qatar have
signed security agreements with the United States and other
Western countries.
</P>
<P>
Addressing today's meeting, Syrian Foreign Minister Farouq
al-Shara stressed the importance of holding the meeting under the
three challenges, the deadlock in the Middle East peace process
because of Israel's intransigent policy, the Turkish-Israeli
alliance and the fact that Arab states are in urgent need of
solidarity.
</P>
<P>
A military training agreement signed by Turkey and Israel in
February 1996 generated fear in Middle East countries that Turkey
was aligning itself with the Jewish state against Syria and other
Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
Al-Shara criticized the U.S. for its participation in the
Turkish-Israeli naval maneuvers recently conducted in the
Mediterranean Sea, ignoring the fact that Israel adopts a policy
that rejects the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian Foreign Minister underlined the necessity of
boosting Arab solidarity to achieve a fair and overall peace in
the region, voicing support of Arab states for the Palestinian
people to obtain their legitimate rights, including
self-determination and establishing an independent state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970625.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China Greeting Hong Kong's Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Although it has been hit by
heavy rainstorms over the last couple of days, the enthusiasm of
people in Guangzhou, the capital of south China's Guangdong
province, for greeting Hong Kong's return has not been dampened.
</P>
<P>
The red five-star national flag, the red regional flag of Hong
Kong with the bauhinia flower, and bunting can be seen everywhere
in the city.
</P>
<P>
Banners with the words "Erasing the 150-year disgrace and
greeting Hong Kong's return", or "Hong Kong will have a more
splendid future", hang along various streets.
</P>
<P>
Parks are competing with each other in decorations. A floral
design with 1,997 fresh flowers in People's Park expresses
people's joyful feelings, while Culture Park offers exhibitions of
painting and calligraphy, and a paper-cutting show.
</P>
<P>
People have been busy watching entertainment activities since
April. Many elderly people from Guangzhou and Hong Kong took part
in a gala celebration. Acrobatics also gave an evening party. The
film "Opium War" on the war that resulted in Hong Kong's being
ceded to Britain, has attracted many movie-goers.
</P>
<P>
And 10,000 actors and actresses will stage a grand performance
on June 30. Another group of actors and actresses are rehearsing a
song and dance performance entitled "Centennial Dream Comes True."
Guangzhou also invited Yan Liangkun, one of China's best known
conductors, to conduct the 1997 Guangzhou Concert on July 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
