<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: Return of HK to China, Step in Right </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif said today that "the return of Hong Kong (to China) is a
step in the right direction and a model for other nations to reach
agreements on thorny issues through negotiations."
</P>
<P>
The Prime Minister made the remarks here during an exclusive
interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The concept of "one country, two systems", put forward by the
late senior Chinese Leader Deng Xiaoping, will certainly reunite
the Chinese nation despite different economic systems, Sharif
said.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan believes in "one China" and hopes that all the
Chinese territories will return to the motherland in the same
manner as Hong Kong and Macao," said the Prime Minister.
</P>
<P>
The return of Hong Kong to China is a great event in the
history of development of the Chinese nation, said Sharif, adding
that "we are happy and congratulate the Chinese nation on the
impending return of Hong Kong  on June 30 (at midnight), 1997 to
be followed two years later by the return of Macao."
</P>
<P>
In answering a question about the prosperity and stability of
Hong Kong after its return to China, the Prime Minister said, "we
believe that Hong Kong will continue to prosper and remain stable
after its return to the motherland. Hong Kong will continue to
enjoy the position of international financial and trade center."
</P>
<P>
"The fast growth of the Chinese economy would contribute to
enhancing further the current status of Hong Kong," he added.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that "the peaceful return of Hong Kong to its
motherland under the pattern of "one country, two systems" is a
good model for other nations to emulate."
</P>
<P>
To a question about Pakistan's current trade with Hong Kong and
ideas of furthering the economic and trade ties with the region,
the Prime Minister said, "Pakistan and Hong Kong have
traditionally enjoyed very sound trading relations. Hong Kong has
emerged as the second most important export market for Pakistan
after the United States."
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan's exports to Hong Kong rose by more than 50 percent
during the last financial year," the Prime Minister pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The Prime Minister expressed his belief that "with the
burgeoning Chinese economy backing Hong Kong, Pakistan-Hong Kong
trade and economic relations will receive a further fillip in the
years ahead."
</P>
<P>
Talking about the latest round of foreign secretary-level talks
between Pakistan and India, Sharif said he is satisfied with the
result. "it is a positive sign," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Prime Minister expressed his belief that with the
"political will and sincerity", all outstanding issues between
Pakistan and India will be solved through negotiations.
</P>
<P>
During the interview, the Prime Minister spoke highly of the
achievements made by China in the construction of its national
economy.
</P>
<P>
Sharif said that he has visited China several times both as
prime minister and leader of the opposition, and witnessed for
himself the fast economic progress made by China in recent years.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
