<DOCNO> XIE19970625.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong to Introduce Bilingual Legal System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
This will help to steer Hong Kong in the direction towards a
more democratic society of rule of law, said Tony Yen Yuen-ho, a
law draftsman of the Legal Department.
</P>
<P>
He said, "English has served as the legal language in Hong Kong
for more than 100 years."
</P>
<P>
However, in Hong Kong, primarily a Chinese community where
most citizens do not have a good knowledge of English, a legal
system with English as the legal language lacks transparency and
is sometimes "unfair".
</P>
<P>
With Hong Kong society opening wider, he noted, if the legal
linguistic status of the Chinese language is still subordinate to
English, it will be detrimental to judicial practices and the
maintenance of the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
However, as English is the language for the establishment of
the existing legal system of Hong Kong, as well as an
international commercial language, it is imperative to refer to
the common law system of Hong Kong from legal cases and legal
documents of other regions where common law is practiced.
</P>
<P>
It is, therefore, necessary to continue to use English in
formulating and enforcing laws, the law expert noted.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong began to use both English and Chinese to formulate
laws in 1986. In 1989, the first bilingual law was enacted.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the translation into Chinese of the
previously-formulated 530 laws was finished in April this year.
</P>
<P>
In fact, basic courts in Hong Kong began to use Chinese long
time ago. Now some intermediate courts have also begun to do so.
</P>
<P>
According to Yen, owing to technical problems, the bilingual
legal system should be practiced step by step.
</P>
<P>
He urged judges, lawyers and legal scholars to use Chinese as
much as possible in their work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970625.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 11:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PKK Kills 3 Turkish Soldiers in Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Three Turkish soldiers were killed
and four others wounded late Tuesday night in an armed attack by
rebels of the Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) in southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported today that a
group of the PKK militants raided a petrol pumping station in
Raman region of Batman province in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The wounded soldiers have been hospitalized, said the report.
</P>
<P>
It added that the Turkish security forces started large-scale
military operations in a bid to capture the PKK rebels who
escaped from the scene in the region.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been staging armed attacks against the Turkish
soldiers in southeastern Turkey since the Turkish military
launched its cross-border operations in pursuit of the PKK rebels
in northern Iraq on May 14.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's massive military campaign followed a request for aid
by Iraq's Kurdistan Democratic Party (KDP) to sweep the PKK
members out of the region.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish military has said that at least 2,500 PKK
militants have been killed in the attack, which was accused by
many as an incursion into northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting a separatist war, which has claimed
over 23,000 lives in eastern and southeastern Turkey since August
1984. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970625.0136 </DOCNO>
