<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK, France Sign Agreement on Cooperation Against Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong and France signed here
today an anti-crime agreement which will remain in force beyond
July 1.
</P>
<P>
Putting their signatures on the agreement were Secretary for
Security Peter Lai, on behalf of the Hong Kong Government, and
Consul-General of France to Hong Kong Thierry Dana, on behalf of
the French Government.
</P>
<P>
The Agreement on Mutual Legal Assistance in Criminal Matters
(MLA agreement) is the third of its kind Hong Kong has signed on
international cooperation against crime.
</P>
<P>
The first one was signed with Australia in September 1996 and
the second one with the United States in April 1997.
</P>
<P>
Major kinds of assistance covered by the agreement include:
taking of evidence, searching for and seizing items which are
relevant to criminal matters, transferring persons, including
prisoners, between the two jurisdictions, and confiscating the
proceeds of crime.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the signing ceremony, Lai said, "The signing of the
third MLA agreement will send a powerful message that we are
committed to fighting international crime."
</P>
<P>
He added that the agreement had been endorsed by the
Sino-British Joint Liaison Group, and would remain in force beyond
the handover. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970625.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Voter Registration Re-Extended in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The Electoral Commission of Kenya
has extended voter registration for another six days starting
from today till Monday with more than seven million Kenyans
having registered.
</P>
<P>
Z. Chesoni, the chairman of the commission, said in a
statement Tuesday evening that the decision came in the wave of
appeals for more time from all corners of the country.
</P>
<P>
A total of 7,241,582 voters had registered up to June 22,
excluding returns from seven constituencies which have not been
received, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The commission believes the Monday and Tuesday, June 23 and
24, figures will lift the total to over eight million registered
voters at June 24," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said he had witnessed crowds of would-be voters waiting to
register at the registration centers and also considered the need
to give an opportunity to patients admitted to hospitals to
register as voters.
</P>
<P>
Long queues were seen outside the registration centers in
eight constituencies in Nairobi in the last three days.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that there was a mad rush for voter
registration countrywide once again to beat the Tuesday deadline.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time the commission extends the deadline.
The first was from June 22 to 24. The registration started on May
19.
</P>
<P>
The commission originally expected there would be about 10
million registered voters around the eastern African country by
the end of the registration.
</P>
<P>
However, only seven million Kenyans registered as voters
before the last general election in 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
