<DOCNO> XIE19970625.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong to Be Much Cleaner in Future: Environmental Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Leung Po-Wing, secretary for
Planning, environment and lands, expressed his full confidence in
Hong Kong's future environment, which, he noted, will be much
cleaner and better still.
</P>
<P>
"We have made Hong Kong cleaner after years of strenuous
effort," he said at a news briefing held at the Hong Kong
Exhibition and Convention Center.
</P>
<P>
On air pollution control, he explained, the government has
divided Hong Kong into 10 atmospheric control zones, with each
having set its qualitative goal.
</P>
<P>
Satisfactory results have been attained by imposing limits on
the use of solid and liquid fuel to reduce the sulphur contents of
fuel in use in factories, spreading the use of lead-free gas and
catalytic devices and banning the use of fluoride which is harmful
to ozonosphere, he said.
</P>
<P>
To date, the rate of sulphuric contents in the air has lowered
by 80 percent and that of lead by 70 percent, he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Leung said, traffic noise has been alleviated thanks
to the improvement of designs for architectural structures and
installation of sound-insulation boards and shelter covers and use
of sound-reducing road materials. The government has erected sound
insulation boards with a total length of 6.4 km on some key roads.
And the railway department has invested 100 million US dollars on
projects for reducing traffic pollution.
In addition, some 8,000 classrooms with relatively serious noise
pollution have been equipped with sound-insulation and air
conditioning facilities.
</P>
<P>
In the early 1980s, the secretary recalled, Hong Kong
discharged two million tons of sewage and 100,000 tons of liquid
chemical wastes into the Victoria Harbor each year. Half of the
sewage wastes was untreated before being discharged into the
harbor.
</P>
<P>
However, the proportion of heavily-polluted water has dropped
from 25 percent in 1989 to the present 10 percent whereas the rate
of fine-quality water has risen from 18 percent to 38 percent,
said Leung, who is to take the same job in the government of the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) upon its
establishment on July 1.
</P>
<P>
On future development, he said, Hong Kong is formulating an
overall plan based on environmental evaluation and will add three
garbage-filling grounds.
</P>
<P>
To date, a sewage disposal works has gone into operation on the
stonecutter Island, and it is now able to treat 25 percent of the
sewage in the western part of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, a deep-sea tunnel is being built at the Victoria
Harbor to collect the sewage wastes at sea, which will be moved to
the Stonecutter Island for disposal.
</P>
<P>
Upon the completion of the tunnel in 1999, 70 percent of the
liquid wastes will have treated before its discharge into the
Victoria Harbor.
</P>
<P>
New technology has offered new channels for environment
protection. Hong Kong's main objective is to work for a sustained
development while maintaining high standards in its environmental
Protection, Leung said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
