<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Turns to Import for Fuel Scarcity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria has concluded arrangements
to import refined oil from Cote d'Ivoire to ease the acute fuel
scarcity that has trapped the country in the last five months.
</P>
<P>
The development follows an order of the head of state, General
Sani Abacha Monday to end the fuel crisis in 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
Local media said it is ironic for Nigeria to import fuel from
Cote d'Ivoire, for the latter gets the bulk of its crude oil from
Nigeria and has only one privately-owned refinery, whereas
Nigeria has four state-owned ones.
</P>
<P>
Report also said that Nigeria has contacted Ghana for fuel
import, though it is doubtful that Ghana has got additional fuel
to export, as it also has only one refinery, with a daily
capacity of 100,000 barrels.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria, the world's No.6 largest crude oil producer, has been
suffering from periodic fuel scarcity in the last few years, due
to its illing refinery industry.
</P>
<P>
The latest fuel scarcity, starting from late January and with
a short period of limit about one months ago, has become a
nationwide crisis with paralyzing effect on people's life and the
national economy.
</P>
<P>
It also led to hot criticism of the oil minister, Dan Etete,
from the finance minister, Anthony Ani and other senior
government officials, last week.
</P>
<P>
In the heat of the crisis, the head of state interfered on
Monday at the Council of State meeting, ordering immediate import
to end the crisis and a rescue to the refineries for a lasting
solution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
