country, where classes of Chinese language are offered after
school or during weekends. In the past few weeks, lectures on Hong
Kong's history and geography were given, and oratorical contests
on Hong Kong were organized in these schools.
</P>
<P>
Now all the autographs have been gathered in Columbus, Ohio,
where the Chinese School Association in the United States (CSAUS)
is headquartered. They were finally bound into a big album which
also includes the photos of many signers.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a huge Chinese national flag, 15 meters long and 7
meters wide, has been made in Los Angeles and ready for shipment.
</P>
<P>
In a few days a delegation led by CSAUS president Jim J. Wang
will take the flag and album to Hong Kong, where a ceremony of
handing over the gifts is scheduled on June 30.
</P>
<P>
Wang said that many American children studying in the Chinese
schools also signed their names together with their Chinese
classmates.
</P>
<P>
"The kids, both Chinese and American, have studied the Chinese
characters for a short time so cannot handle them very well," Wand
said. "But their autographs are very beautiful to me." 
