<HEADLINE> Shanghai People Active in Community Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 25 (Xinhua) -- In a true rekindling of community
spirit in the heart of the city, some notices posted in
residential areas of Shanghai are advertising voluntary services
being offered by ordinary citizens.
</P>
<P>
And the do-gooders are not few and far between, according to
surveys. Shanghai is believed to have around 720,000 residents who
are willing to give a helping hand to their fellow citizens.
</P>
<P>
Volunteers, apparently, come from all sections of
society. There are government officials, workers, businessmen,
teachers and students, children and retirees. And they will do
virtually anything to help a neighbor: clean an apartment, repair
a bike, mind the kids, fix the TV, even advise on legal
matters. What's more, they do it for free.
</P>
<P>
A resident from the Jinyangyuan district said all families
there had taken care of the flowers and trees in neighborhood
gardens, and over 4,000 yuan in donations has been collected to
buy 3,000 more saplings with which to green the area.
</P>
<P>
"Community volunteers are breaking down walls of indifference
lying between urban residents by offering a helping hand," said a
city official, Xu Deming.  
</P>
