<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers of west African
countries are to gather in Conakry, Guinea, on June 26 to discuss
the Sierra Leonean crisis, the New Nigerian reported today.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is to be held at the instance of Nigeria's head of
state, General Sani Abacha who is the current chairman of the
Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS).
</P>
<P>
The official newspaper quoted a Nigerian foreign ministry
statement as saying that the ministers are expected to assess the
situation in Sierra Leone, where a coup overthrew the elected
civilian government on May 25.
</P>
<P>
It is also expected to recommend strategies to be adopted in
resolving the political crisis in that country, said the
statement issued Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's Foreign Affairs Minister Tom Ikimi left Abuja,
capital of Nigeria, for consultation with some countries' heads
of government in the sub-region ahead of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
During the visits, Ikimi would discuss an ECOWAS framework for
resolving the Sierra Leone crisis, said the statement without any
details.
</P>
<P>
Ikimi visited Guniea and Cote d'Ivoire early last week as part
of a concerted effort towards an ECOWAS common approach to the
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Before returning to Nigeria, the minister is expected to stop
over in Monrovia, the Liberian capital, to assess the progress
being made in preparation for the general election scheduled for
July 19 this year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the eight French-speaking countries in the
sub-region have broken their silence on the coup in
English-speaking Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
In a declaration issued at the end of their one-day summit in
Lome, Togo, Sunday, the eight countries categorically condemned
the military take over in Sierra Leone
</P>
<P>
They said they will not recognize the military junta and
called for the immediate restoration of constitutional rule in
that country.
</P>
<P>
Some troops of ECOMOG, the ECOWAS peacekeeping force operating in
Liberia have been sent to Sierra Leone in the wake of the May 25 coup.
Nigeria is the main contributor of the force.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
