<DOCNO> XIE19970625.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea Predicts Booming in Trade, Commerce With HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 25 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's trade and commerce
with Hong Kong will rise steadily after Hong Kong's return to
China on July 1, said the Ministry of Trade, Industry and Energy
today.
</P>
<P>
The ministry, in a report outlining the situation of Hong Kong
after July 1, said the prediction is based on Hong Kong's
uninterrupted economic buoyance, China's promise on the "one
country, two systems" framework and the capital inflow from
adjacent areas.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean government has decided to maintain existing
trade and commerce policies toward Hong Kong after July 1, the
ministry said.
</P>
<P>
It said that China's high economic growth rate would clear the
way for South Korea's increased shipments via Hong Kong, while
direct shipments to Hong Kong will also be bolstered along with a
sharp rise in demand for various facilities and technologies
related to the expansion of infrastructure investments in Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
There are limits to South Korea's bid to invest in Hong Kong's
manufacturing sector because of Hong Kong's narrow market and high
production costs, but South Korea's joint ventures with Hong
Kong's ethnic Chinese is considered a foundation for business
operations in China, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The ministry promised to extend support to help maintain
cooperation with Hong Kong in international organizations,
including Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation after the power
transfer, so as to promote the trade and commerce relations
continuously.
</P>
<P>
Last year, South Korea posted a trade surplus of 10 billion US
dollars with Hong Kong and registered a surplus of 4.334 billion
dollars in the first five months of this year, statistics show.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
