<HEADLINE> S. Korean Companies View HK as Bridge to Chinese Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 25 (Xinhua) -- South Korean companies are expecting
to use Hong Kong as a bridge for their entry into the Chinese
market.
</P>
<P>
The latest surveys show most of South Korean firms believe that
after Hong Kong's return to China on July 1, the free economic
system, on which Hong Kong's prosperity has been based, will
remain unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The integration of the markets of Hong Kong and China's inland
areas would create new opportunities for South Korean companies,
they said.
</P>
<P>
South Korean companies are likely to increase direct investment
and trade with China and use Hong Kong as a financial and
information communication base.
</P>
<P>
The Samsung Group, which would push ahead with its plan to
connect its financial and information communication functions in
Hong Kong with manufacturing units in China.
</P>
<P>
The Daewoo Group, which will set up three offices in Hong Kong,
Beijing and Shanghai respectively, plans to increase its
investment in southern China with Hong Kong as its hub.
</P>
<P>
The Hyundai Group looks into the possible construction boom in
Guangdong Province after Hong Kong's return to China. In an effort
to improve its business, the group will establish an office in
Hong Kong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
