<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- The French parliament Tuesday began a debate on a government
plan to control distribution of family allowances, while hundreds
of supporters of family rights groups demonstrated outside the
parliament building. Nicole Notat, secretary general of the French
Democratic Confederation of Labor, has called on the government to
suspend the measure.
</P>
<P>
-- Former French Finance Minister Alain Madellin has become the
king of French liberals after being elected president of the
Republican Party, rebaptized Liberal Democracy party, at an
extraordinary session of the party attended by 3,000 militants in
the middle-class district of Levallois outside Paris.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- By presenting the general lines of his policy, the new
Minister of National Education, Research and Technology Claude
Allegre vowed to decentralize and "debureaucratize" the school
personnel management and science-technology research hierarchy of
France. He is also going to re-examine France's school competition
system, which costs one billion francs (170 million U.S. dollars)
each year.
</P>
<P>
-- After Canada, Belgium and Italy are now under a shock caused
by press revelation on the brutality of their soldiers serving in
the U.N. 1992-1994 "Restore Hope" operation in Somalia.
</P>
<P>
The Belgium defense ministry plans to dissolve one army unit if
it is proved that its soldiers systematically carried out acts of
atrocity, while two Italian army generals have resigned after
pictures were published showing Italian soldiers torturing and
raping Somalians. 
</P>
