<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deregulation, Anti-dumping Top EU-Japan Summit Agenda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
THE HAGUE, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The annual European Union-Japan
summit meeting started today in the Dutch capital of the Hague
with Japan's program of deregulation and EU's anti-dumping
measures at top of the agenda.
</P>
<P>
The summit, attended by Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto, European Commission President Jacques Santer and Dutch
Prime Minister and current EU President Wim Kok, is the sixth
since the two sides met for their first summit of this kind in The
Hague in 1991.
</P>
<P>
The EU is expected to put more pressure on Japan to speed up
its three-year deregulation program.
</P>
<P>
European Commission officials said that the latest revision of
the deregulation program, announced by Japan in March, was
"disappointing."
</P>
<P>
Although Japan's revised package covers areas like financial
services, communications, housing, distribution, transport,
energy, labor and education, the commission complained that
overall progress had been limited.
</P>
<P>
The EU is also expected to call on Japan to further its reform,
possibly by launching another far-reaching multi-annual
deregulation program.
</P>
<P>
In turn, Japan will press the EU on its increasing use of
anti-dumping measures against cheap imports, a practice which
Tokyo sees as a veiled protectionism.
</P>
<P>
The summit is reported to cover issues including the EU
Amsterdam Summit held last week, the EU expansion to central and
eastern Europe and the European single currency.
</P>
<P>
It will also discuss the talks about the World Trade
Organization and the Asia-Europe meeting scheduled for next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970625.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tung Chee Hwa, A Man Devoted to Hong Kongers' Well-being (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 25 (Xinhua) -- "Seven-Eleven", is a duration of
business hours a kind of shops especially extend to satisfy the
needs of customers. The term can now be used to describe a work
day of Tung Chee Hwa, chief executive of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR).
</P>
<P>
Tung has become a busy man who are sought after by press
circles ever since he received the letter of appointment from
Chinese Premier Li Peng in mid-December, 1996.
</P>
<P>
Entrusted with a historic mission, Tung has been busy
conferring officials of the British Hong Kong government, meeting
with ordinary residents and listening to their views, and
addressing varied functions daily over the past 190 days.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he raced against the time in forming the future
HKSAR government. He has always been busy attending meetings,
making speeches, reading documents and interviewing with
journalists from all over the world.
</P>
<P>
He has left his footprints everywhere in Hong Kong, either in
the Hong Kong Exhibition and Convention Center, or in communities
or hotels.
</P>
<P>
Tung, 60, had resigned from his posts as a member of the
British-Hong Kong Executive Council and chairman and chief
executive officer of the Orient Overseas (International) Ltd.,
before he decided to run for the office of the first chief
executive of the HKSAR. And with the fortitude, and the sense of
resourcefulness and self-confidence fostered in his business
career over decades, he took the responsibilities of the first
Chief Executive of the Hong Kong SAR.
</P>
<P>
He was committed to the formation of the HKSAR Government, a
key link in ensuring the smooth transition in Hong Kong. The task
he has undertaken is unprecedented in history and very
complicated. A great many difficulties are involved, and there are
still too many things to attend to.
</P>
<P>
A staff at the Chief Executive Office said, "Tung was too busy
with his work. He is at office from seven o'clock in the morning
to eleven in evening daily, without a single day off every week."
</P>
<P>
Though Tung is a football fan, but now has no time for the
hobby, the staffer added.
</P>
<P>
In his own words, Tung said he is "busy all day long with no
holidays" and his hair and eyebrow are "greying a lot".
Nevertheless, he is working dedicatedly and with willingness to
the future of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Local people held that the formation of the HKSAR Government
proceeded smoothly since Tung was appointed by the Central
Government as the first Chief Executive.
</P>
<P>
To date, Tong has nominated 23 principal officials for the
first government of the HKSAR, formed the first Executive Council,
the Court of Final Appeal and High Court and appointed members of
the provisional Urban council and the Provisional municipal
Council and the district board, paving way for the smooth
operation of the HKSAR Government on July 1.
</P>
<P>
He formed his cabinet in accordance with his consistent work
style of "resourcefulness and proceeding steadily and in a
well-planned way". It took him over a month to have separate
meetings with more than 20 senior officials of the British Hong
Kong government, soliciting their opinions on the operation of the
future government, routine work procedures and division of work.
Many of them were impressed by his sincerity and firmness.
</P>
<P>
The objective of turning Hong Kong into a stable, equitable,
compassionate and democratic society with clarity of direction and
unity under the principle "One country, two systems" proposed by
Tung Chee Hwa has won wide recognition and endorsement from the
whole community.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970625.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
