<DOCNO> XIE19970625.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Optimism Prevails in Symposium on HK's Future (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Hong Kong's return to China should have the effect of adding a
large new dimension to our market without taking any of its
existing international and regional role," Cheng told the
conference.
</P>
<P>
With the backing of the economic hinterland of China, he added,
Hong Kong should be better positioned than now to increase the
breadth and sophistication of its range of financial products and
services, thus enhancing its "critical mass" as an international
financial center.
</P>
<P>
Henry Tang, chairman of the Federation of Hong Kong Industries,
expressed a similar view in a written speech titled "The Hong Kong
- China Nexus" presented to the symposium.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the "one country, two systems" concept, Tang
pointed out, Hong Kong will benefit from all of the strengths that
have built Hong Kong to what it is today, and at the same time
"puts us in pole position" to capture opportunities that are
arising across the interior area as its economy steadily opens.
</P>
<P>
Upon its return to China, he noted, Hong Kong's role as the
metropolitan heart of an increasingly affluent south China region
will be greatly enhanced now that the barriers to official contact
are brought down, and Hong Kong will continue to be the main
source of foreign capital inflow for inland businesses.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of Hong Kong's future advantages, Raymond Ch'ien,
chairman of the Industry and Technology Development Council, said
Hong Kong should focus on development of the high-tech sector to
create new advantages for sustained economic development.
</P>
<P>
Differing from Ch'ien's view, David Dodwell, co-author of the
recently published Hong Kong's Advantages, said the Hong Kong's
economy has changed from a manual economy to a knowledge-based
one, and a metropolitan economy with links to China's interior
areas and the region.
</P>
<P>
With services booming and manufacturing value-added increasing,
Dodwell argued that Hong Kong's future lies in retaining its
present economic pattern.
</P>
<P>
Observers here pointed out that the positive mood displayed
during the symposium embodies the optimism prevailing in Hong
Kong's business community.
</P>
<P>
Latest surveys conducted by the American and Canadian chambers
of commerce in Hong Kong among their member companies show that 95
percent of American companies see the business environment for the
next five years as either "very favorable" or "favorable", while
99 percent of the Canadian respondents will stay in Hong Kong
beyond the year 2000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970625.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Optimism Prevails in Symposium on HK's Future (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 25 -- Optimism about Hong Kong's future played
the main tune during a two-day symposium on Hong Kong's continued
prosperity after its return to China on July 1.
</P>
<P>
Political and business figures, from both Hong Kong and other
parts of the world, envisioned a politically stable and
economically prosperous Hong Kong while addressing the Symposium
on Countdown to 1997: Roadmap to Hong Kong's Continued Prosperity.
</P>
<P>
The symposium, which closed here yesterday, was sponsored by
Far Eastern Economic Review, one of the most influential business
weeklies in Asia.
</P>
<P>
In a keynote speech at the symposium, Lee Kuan Yew, Senior
Minister of Singapore, predicted that the Chinese leadership will
observe the Sino-British Joint Declaration and the Basic Law,
which are in China's national interest, and will go all out to
show that Hong Kong can thrive and prosper after its return to
China.
</P>
<P>
He warned that those pressing China on Hong Kong "may find they
have helped to frustrate themselves, because China will make
doubly sure it does not breach the Joint Declaration and the Basic
Law."
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the "one country, two system" policy pursued
by the Chinese government, Hong Kong will maintain for 50 years
its existing economic and political structures after its return to
China, enjoying a high degree of autonomy.
</P>
<P>
Lee pointed out that public confidence in the economy is
currently at a record high, as reflected in the strength of the
stock and property markets, while the international community
shares this confidence.
</P>
<P>
He told the symposium that a recent survey found that over 90
percent of foreign-funded companies in Hong Kong will stay after
the handover, which cited favorable banking and financial
facilities, infrastructure, tax regime as the top three
attractions that will remain unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Local business leaders, from the standpoint of their respective
fields, shared Lee's confidence in post-handover Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the symposium on the prospects for Hong Kong's stock
market, Edgar Cheng, chairman of the Stock Exchange of Hong Kong,
noted that the local securities market will not only maintain its
key elements that have made it one of the most successful in the
world, but also benefit from new business opportunities created by
the historic handover.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970625.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Government Rushes Decrees to Save Finance Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government Tuesday pushed
through four executive decrees as urgent measures to help the
troubled finance and property sectors in the country.
</P>
<P>
According to the Government House, one of the decrees was
introduced to amend the bill on finance business to encourage the
mergers of finance firms and allow the core finance company to
hold stakes in other companies for the purpose of acquisition.
</P>
<P>
Another decree was designed to go round the bill on commercial
banks to allow the finance minister to approve foreigners to hold
limited stakes in a commercial bank to help finance firms to seek
foreign partners.
</P>
<P>
It also will allow the finance minister to approve a board
member of commercial bank to be a member of other banks, but for
no more than three years.
</P>
<P>
The third decree aimed to facilitate finance companies to set
up ad-hoc institutes for securitization to help them overcome
their existing funding problems.
</P>
<P>
The fourth decree is on the secondary mortgage corporations.
</P>
<P>
However, local newspapers said that the measures introduced as
executive decrees to go around the legislative procedures are
likely to place the government at unnecessary risk in the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
Some cabinet ministers felt that the measures should have been
introduced in the form of draft bills which would require the
approval of the parliament, instead of executive decrees.
</P>
<P>
Yet new Finance Minister Thanong Bidaya believed that the
measures should be in place urgently in view of the current
situation in the country's finance sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
