<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Suffers Losses from Illegal Motor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 25 (Xinhua) -- At least 1,000 used vehicles
were entering South Africa illegally every month, costing the
motor industry millions of Rand in terms of lost sales, local
daily Business Day reported today.
</P>
<P>
"This is just a conservative estimate," Motor Industries
Federation (MIF) President Oscar Taub was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The illegally imported vehicles originate from various parts
of the world including Europe and the United States, but mainly
from Japan and Korea, he said.
</P>
<P>
Taub said while the MIF could not provide figures on the cost
in monetary terms and possible job losses, the illegal imports
had a negative impact on South Africa's motor industry.
</P>
<P>
The MIF has made several representations to the governement
about the matter, he said.
</P>
<P>
Similar sentiments were echoed by the National Association of
Automobile Manufacturers of South Africa, which appealed the
government to pay an "urgent attention" to the matter.
</P>
<P>
According to the automobile industry sources, new vehicle
sales in South Africa plunged 19 percent in May to 30,610 units,
which is believed to have something to do with illegal import of
motor vehicles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
