<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania to Spend $1.6m on Grain Reserves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The government plans to
spend 1,000 million Tanzania Shillings (about 1.6 million US
Dollars) to boost the Strategy Grain Reserves (SGR), local press
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Deputy Minister for Agriculture and Co-operatives, Pius
Mbawala said that the SGR would start buying grain from farmers
in the first week next month and beef up stocks in order to have
enough food to meet demand in the event of famine.
</P>
<P>
The deputy minister said the SGR seeks to pay better prices to
farmers as an incentive to produce more and stop them from
selling grain to smugglers and unscrupulous middlemen.
</P>
<P>
According to the deputy minister, since the SGR was
established in the country, the government has injected 10,898
million T.Shs. (about 18.2 million U.S. Dollars) into its
coffers.
</P>
<P>
The highest amount came in the 1992/93 season when the
government pumped in 3,757 million T.Shs. (about 6.3 million
U.S. Dollars) and the lowest amount was dished out in the 1996/97
season when the SGR got 400 million T.Shs. (about 666,000
Dollars) only. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
