<HEADLINE> "Tree of Wishes" Reflects Hope of School Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 25 (Xinhua) -- "I hope everybody loves Hong
Kong". The hope was expressed by a middle school student in
Kowloon.
</P>
<P>
First-grader Luk Kar Po of the Mong Kok School for Workers'
Children wrote the message on a piece of heart-shaped paper, then
put it on a "tree of wishes" on a wall of the school hall.
</P>
<P>
As part of the program to celebrate Hong Kong's return to
China, the 980 students in the school erected the four-m-tall
"tree of wishes" adorned with heart-shaped paper in red, yellow
and green, on which they wrote their hopes on and expectations for
the future Hong Kong Special Administrative Region.
</P>
<P>
One message reads that "I hope that everyone will become
prettier day by day, and Hong Kong's economy will grow steadily."
</P>
<P>
One student expressed the hope that Hong Kong will continue to
be stable and prosperous in the future, another hoped that HKSAR
Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa will govern Hong Kong successfully,
and still another wished for peace in the world.
</P>
<P>
Lai Tak Keung, a teacher of the Chinese language, said the
school established last September a preparatory committee for
activities to celebrate Hong Kong's return to China. The
activities include a competition for design of handover souvenirs,
and a poem composition contest.
</P>
<P>
The school, founded in 1946, raises the Chinese national flag
on every National Day, which falls on October 1, and teaches its
students to love the motherland, the people, labor, science and
public properties.  
</P>
</TEXT>
