<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Stage Recovery To Close Firmer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
staged a late recovery to close higher, with broad base investor
confidence renewed after a positive turnaround on Wall Street
overnight.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index finished 16.7 points firmer
at 2705.1, undoing yesterday's 17.9 point fall, while the Dow
Jones industrial average finished 153.80 points higher to 7,758.06
overnight.
</P>
<P>
The local market recovered from the morning low of 2688.4.
</P>
<P>
A Sydney-based broker said the rally on Wall Street and the
local market's subsequent fall yesterday after the Dow Jones
Industrial Average's plunge was regarded as an over-reaction to
comments from Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto.
</P>
<P>
Lance Jones' broker Hamish Dee said while there was a degree of
book-squaring going on in preparation for the end of the financial
year, the market had also received an injection from overseas
investors.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index closed up 31.4 points at 4259.7,
while the all resources index lifted 4.7 points to 1505.8.
</P>
<P>
On the resources front, oil and gas group Woodside was a star
performer, piling on 73.7 cents to close at 11.207 Australian
dollars -- having reached an intraday high of 11.30 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Market bellwether BHP shed 15 cents to 19.25 Australian dollars
while diverse resources giant Rio Tinto was up 33.6 cents at 22.89
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Weakened by lower overseas prices, the gold index slid 18.3
points to 1461.8.
</P>
<P>
In Sydney, gold bullion was trading at 337.90 US dollars per
fine ounce, compared to yesterday's close of 339.75 US dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 393.19 million shares worth 999.80
million Australian dollars (749.85 million US dollars), with rises
of 658 outnumbering falls of 568. 
</P>
</TEXT>
