<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNDP Urges People-rooted Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 25 (Xinhua) -- An official of the United Nations
Development Programme (UNDP) warned Tuesday that sustainability
of development efforts is at risk unless they are rooted within
people and their communities.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a five-day workshop on participatory approaches and
partnerships in Bulawayo, the second largest city of Zimbabwe,
UNDP assistant representative Duduzile Chandiwana said the agency
had learnt that participatory relationships with communities had
to be changed.
</P>
<P>
She said there was need for a change of strategy if
development programmes, under which millions of dollars were
spent, were to succeed.
</P>
<P>
She said participation was one of the most effective
strategies for change and policy reform.
</P>
<P>
Experience had taught the agency that development initiatives
were sustained where communities were empowered to take the lead
and control their agenda.
</P>
<P>
She said the UNDP's major role now was poverty alleviation,
and that the agency was taking a more focused approach to human
resource development.
</P>
<P>
"We used to be a jack-of-all-trades, but now we have to change
the way we do business," she said.
</P>
<P>
The workshop which began Monday is being attended by 70
delegates from Angola, Eritrea, Lesotho, Malawi, Mauritius,
Mozambique, Namibia, South Africa, Swaziland, Zambia and
Zimbabwe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
