<HEADLINE> 204 Philippine Migrant Workers to be Repatriated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 25 (Xinhua) -- At least 204 Philippine migrant
workers, who were recently arrested by the Malaysian authorities
for "illegally" staying there, will be repatriated to the
Philippines this week, government officials said here today.
</P>
<P>
The 204 Filipinos are among those who have been arrested
earlier by the Malaysian immigration authorities following its
crackdown on "illegal aliens," officials in the Foreign Affairs
Department said.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Embassy in Malaysia reported that there are
113,400 Philippine migrant workers working or staying in Malaysia
without proper permit.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian government has given these illegal migrant
workers until May 31, 1997 to register to its immigration bureau
for proper documentation. But some of the 113,400 illegal migrant
workers failed to comply with the requirements by the Malaysian
government before the deadline for registration.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Affairs Department officials said that the Philippines
and Malaysia recently agreed that those who failed to register for
documentation will be eventually repatriated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
