<HEADLINE> Red Lanterns Hanging High along Beijing Main Streets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 25 (Xinhua) -- With the handover countdown well into
single figures, Beijing is brightening itself up with giant
red lanterns to celebrate Hong Kong's return.
</P>
<P>
According to Chinese tradition, red lanterns carry jubilant and
auspicious meanings, and people usually hang them outside buildings
and in their homes on high days and holidays, most notably at
Spring Festival and on October 1st, China's National Day.
</P>
<P>
In Tian'anmen Square, some 60 red lanterns measuring 1.1 meters
in diameter and two meters in height have been positioned around
the square, while another 100 will be hung on the two sides of the
digital countdown clock outside the Museum of Chinese History.
</P>
<P>
A few hundred meters to the east of the square, six workers wrestled
in sweltered heat to position five 1.8-meter-diameter red lanterns
outside the main door of the Beijing Hotel.
</P>
<P>
Wang Youqing, an electrician at the hotel, said the
lanterns seemed much bigger and brighter than the ones hung
before.
</P>
<P>
Lanterns, big and small, are also catching the eye along the
city's main shopping streets: Wangfujing, Xidan and Dongdan.
</P>
<P>
For special symbolism, exactly 1,997 big red lanterns have been
hung along the four-kilometer stretch of road between Xuanwumen
and Xinjiekou.
</P>
<P>
Zhai Yuliang, a manager at the Beijing Artistic Red Lantern
Factory, is delighted at the unseasonal demand for red
lanterns. Business is so hot that factory workers have been
working overtime to turn out more lanterns. In the past month the
factory has produced more than 4,000 red lanterns for some 1,000
customers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
