<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ramos Urged to Suspend Operations Against Kidnappers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Regional officials in Mindanao have
appealed to President Fidel Ramos for immediate suspension of the
military operations against suspected kidnappers in the southern
part of the country, an official said today.
</P>
<P>
Ustadz Murshi Ibrahim, chief of staff of the Autonomous Region
in Muslim Mindanao, said the appeal was contained in a strongly
worded resolution addressed to the President through Defense
Secretary Renato de Villa.
</P>
<P>
The appeal said the recent operations by government troops
against the suspected kidnappers, Moro Islamic Liberation Front
(MILF) rebels, had led to the evacuation of thousands of civilians
in Maguindanao and North Cotabato provinces.
</P>
<P>
The military intensified its assaults after 200 MILF rebels
held hostage 43 employees of the Philippine Oil Co. on June 16.
Since last Friday, the two sides have been trading mortar fires,
killing at least 30 rebels and three soldiers.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that government troops have closed in on the
MILF's second biggest camp in the region. As a result, both the
rebels and the military are sending fresh forces there, fueling
speculation that the clashes will escalate.
</P>
<P>
The continuation of military offensive may further aggravate
the situation in Mindanao and result in an open armed conflict
between government troops and MILF rebels, Ibrahim said.
</P>
<P>
He added that aside from the suspension of military operations,
the regional officials are also demanding for the immediate
withdrawal of government troops in areas of conflict.
</P>
<P>
Nur Misuari, chairman of the Autonomous Region in Muslim
Mindanao, had earlier proposed the two sides calm down to forge a
general truce to prevent the collapse of their peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The MILF broke away from the mainstream Moro National
Liberation Front (MNLF) headed by Misuari in 1970s. Its leaders
had threatened to quit peace talks with the government if
government troops continue the operations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
