<DOCNO> XIE19970625.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hkhk-Interview: Pakistani Diplomat on Hong Kong's Future By Shi Xiaofan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hong Kong, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The Pakistani envoy here said
Hong Kong is important for Pakistan economically and expressed
confidence in its future.
</P>
<P>
"As Hong Kong will continue to prosper as an international trade
and financial center after it returns to China, its attractions
for foreign investors are bound to grow," said Mr. Puri, Pakistan
Consul-General in Hong Kong, in a recent interview in his China
Resources Building office.
</P>
<P>
According to Mr. Puri, Hong Kong has emerged as Pakistan's
second largest trading partner, next only to the United States. In
1996, Pakistan exported 833 million US dollars worth of goods to
Hong Kong, up 55 percent over the previous year. In the same year,
Pakistan imported 79 million US dollars worth of goods from Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
Apart from direct bilateral trade, Hong Kong also serves as an
important base for Pakistan's entrepot trade, he said. "The bulk
of Pakistan's trade with the United States, for example, is done
via Hong Kong," he said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is a prime venue for doing business thanks to its
status as an international trade and financial center and the
presence there of numerous multinationals, he said.
Interaction with international portfolio investors and fund
managers present in Hong Kong has generated a great deal of
support for the Pakistani stock market, Mr. Puri said.
</P>
<P>
Mr. Puri is also a trade expert with working experiences in
Pakistan's Ministry of Commerce, the World Trade Organization and
as consul-general in Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
"I agree that my appointment in the economically-important Hong
Kong is partly due to my experiences in the trade and commercial
sector", the 46-year-old consul-general said.
</P>
<P>
"Since many of Hong Kong-based multinationals are involved in
textile trade, this market is an extremely important one for
Pakistan," he said.
Pakistan is a cotton-growing country where cotton-related
products account for 65 percent of the country's total exports, he
said.
"That is why Hong Kong has also played an important role in
Pakistan's textiles trade in the world, and long-term prospects in
this regard are good," he said.
</P>
<P>
Since he came to Hong Kong two years ago, his consulate has
helped at least 15 multinationals with regional headquarters in
Hong Kong to open representative or liaison offices in Pakistan,
said Mr. Puri.
</P>
<P>
He said Pakistan has begun making many of the world's brand-name
garments in addition to exporting cotton yarn and fabrics, and
Hong Kong has played a role in this, too. "Hong Kong experts are
now working in Pakistan to help garment-makers upgrade their
products," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I just cannot agree to some negative reports on the future of
Hong Kong, since they are not based on the real situation here. On
the contrary, I'm absolutely convinced that, if there are to be
any changes, Hong Kong will change for the better."
</P>
<P>
"Encouraging economic indicators from all sectors, the constant
return of Hong Kong people who earlier emigrated to foreign
countries and the growing presence of multinationals all point to
a bright future here," he said.
 Hong Kong's success is largely due to its proximity with China,
and when Hong Kong returns to China, economic and commercial links
will surely increase and strengthen, he said.
</P>
<P>
In his opinion, the "one country, two systems" is a unique
concept, thanks to which Hong Kong is experiencing a smooth and
painless transition and will continue to be stable and prosperous.
</P>
<P>
"The application of this concept reflects the farsightedness and
pragmatic wisdom of the Chinese leadership," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mr. Puri said his work in Hong Kong is one of the most rewarding
experiences in his career.
</P>
<P>
"It is a matter of great pride for me to witness the historic
moment when, after being under British colonial rule for such a
long time, Hong Kong will be reunited with its motherland," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970625.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Takes Steps to Attract Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government has taken
a number of steps to attract significant amounts of foreign direct
investment, which have started to deliver in this undeveloped
country.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina told the parliament on Tuesday
that to attract foreign direct investment and strengthen the
private sector, her government has taken a number of steps
including tax holiday for five to seven years, and ten years for
the units in the export processing zones. The tax holiday for
power generation will be 15 years.
</P>
<P>
On import duty, there is only 7.5 percent import duty on
machinery and spare parts and no import duty on machinery for 100
percent export-oriented industries.
</P>
<P>
The government allows 100 percent foreign investment and grants
tax exemption on royalty, technical fee and salary of foreign
personnel working in Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said that the country has been divided into
23 blocks to explore gas and oil under production-sharing
contracts, and accords have already been signed for eight blocks.
And eight more blocks are now on offer, she disclosed.
</P>
<P>
She said her government has also set up a law commission to
make the judiciary and legal system up-to-date and an
administration reforms Commission to make the administration
dynamic.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the prime minister said, seminars were arranged in
different countries and she herself invited the foreign investors
attending these seminars to put their money in Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
"I will attend two such kind of seminars during my ensuring
visit to Japan from July 1," she added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
