<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 06:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aspirin Helps Prevent Second Stroke: Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 25 (Xinhua) -- An international study has found
out that aspirin could prevent a second stoke if it is taken by
the patient within 48 hours of the first one.
</P>
<P>
The study, which included Israeli researchers, was carried out
in 36 countries and has studied the cases of 19,435 patients, 114
of them Israelis, the English daily The Jerusalem Post reported
today.
</P>
<P>
It concluded that a dose of at least 300 milligrams of aspirin
taken within 48 hours of the first stroke could prevent the death
of 10 patients or a recurrent stroke for each 1,000 persons who
have undergone a stroke.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Natan Bornstein, head of the unit for cerebrovascular
diseases at Ichilov Hospital in Tel Aviv, was quoted as saying
that aspirin was highly effective in reducing mortality after a
stroke, compared to the blood-thinning drug heparin.
</P>
<P>
When heparin was given in moderate doses, aspirin proved more
effective; and when large doses of heparin were administered, the
patients often suffered cerebral hemorrhages as a result, the
study revealed.
</P>
<P>
Strokes, in which blood vessels in the brain are blocked by a
clot causing oxygen starvation and damage to brain tissue, are the
third most common cause of death in Israel after cardiovascular
diseases and cancer. They are also the main cause of disability
in middle-aged and elderly adults.
</P>
<P>
Borenstein said the research results added an important
contribution to the controversial question of aspirin versus
heparin after a stroke. At least 300 milligrams of aspirin should
be given in the emergency room and immediately after a
clot-induced stroke is diagnosed, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970625.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Opposition Warns Against Move to Rig Bypoll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The opposition Bangladesh
Nationalist Party (BNP) has threatened to launch a campaign to
topple the government if it tries to rig the Manikganj by-election
scheduled for June 30.
</P>
<P>
BNP leader Khaleda Zia told a public meeting in Manikganj
Tuesday that If the government tried to rig the election, tamper
results of the polling or indulge in any other manipulation, such
a movement would be launched to compel it to quit.
</P>
<P>
"I've come here to meet you with a demand, the demand for your
valuable vote. I always consider you as my close kin, so I have
the right to make this demand," said the former prime minister.
</P>
<P>
The Manikganj-3 seat was vacated after the death of BNP
lawmaker Alhaj Nizamuddin Khan in March. The BNP had earlier
announced that it would not contest the by-election under the
present Chief Election Commissioner Abu Hena.
</P>
<P>
The BNP, however, changed its mind early this month and said it
will take part in the bypoll "for the sake of democracy and
following the assurance by the Election commission."
</P>
<P>
Khaleda Zia told the cheering crowd that the government was
destroying the country through its misrule and conspiracies. "This
is the character of the government. It can not be trusted."
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the opposition leader said the government has
ruined the economy of the country within only one year and called
upon the people to resist the government's activities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
