<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central China Province Promotes Farmers' Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Central China's Hunan Province
has lifted 520,000 adult farmers out of illiteracy and trained
them in technical skills over the past two years so that they will
improve their wellbeing.
</P>
<P>
The province has more than 50 million farmers, of whom only
760,000 are still illiterate. Over years of efforts, about a half
of its cities and counties have wiped out illiteracy among the
adults.
</P>
<P>
Governments at all levels in Hunan have set up night schools
for farmers. An example is Lixian County which has opened over 250
night schools in its poverty-stricken villages and has lifted
12,000 farmers out of illiteracy and helped them grasp some
technical skills to earn more money.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a number of grassroots governments have paid
attention to the education of illiterate women who still account
for the bulk of the rural population.
</P>
<P>
Tang Zhixiang, vice-governor of the province, says that it is
an important task of the government to help farmers become
literate, and Hunan will continue to give priority to it.
</P>
<P>
The province is to help another 500,000 illiterate people
receive education this year, according to Tang. 
</P>
</TEXT>
