<DOCNO> XIE19970625.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hkhk - Hong Kong-related Data (9): Central Government Responsible </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Article 13 of the Basic Law
stipulates, "The Central People's Government shall be responsible
for the foreign affairs relating to the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region."
</P>
<P>
Foreign affairs refer to such activities, conducted in the name
of the state by the head of state, the head of government, the
Foreign Ministry, diplomatic representative organizations and
diplomatic delegations, as visits, negotiations, making
representations, issuing diplomatic documents, concluding
treaties, attending international conferences and joining
international organizations.
</P>
<P>
The handling of such state-to-state foreign affairs, in the
name of the state or government with other countries or
international organizations, reflects the sovereignty of a state.
</P>
<P>
These differ in nature from the economic, trade and cultural
contacts between non-state and non-government organizations, which
are unofficial or non-governmental external affairs.
</P>
<P>
As a regional administrative region of China, Hong Kong does
not have the power to handle foreign affairs.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the first section of Article 13 of the Basic Law
makes an explicit stipulation regarding the foreign affairs
relating to Hong Kong that the Central Government handles.
</P>
<P>
Considering that the HKSAR enjoys a high degree of autonomy,
the third section of Article 13 of the Basic Law states: "The
Central People's Government authorizes the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region to conduct relevant external affairs on its
own in accordance with this Law."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970625.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hkhk - Hong Kong-related Data (10): Stationing of Troops in Hong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The central authorities decided
to station troops in Hong Kong in 1997. This embodies state
sovereignty and is out of the need to maintain social order in
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The troops dispatched by the Central People's Government to the
HKSAR will be responsible only for defense affairs, and will not
interfere in the local affairs of the SAR.
</P>
<P>
The social order within the Region will be the responsibility
with the HKSAR Government. The HKSAR may, when necessary, ask the
Central People's Government for assistance from the troops in
maintaining public order and conducting disaster relief
operations.
</P>
<P>
The troops shall abide by national laws as well as laws of the
HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
So far, the expenditure of the British troops in Hong Kong has
been borne by Hong Kong people.
</P>
<P>
After 1997, however, the Central Government will be responsible
for Hong Kong's defense and the Hong Kong people will not have to
pay the military expenses.
</P>
<P>
The military expenditure will be borne by the Central People's
Government in accordance with the Basic Law, which is a special
treatment granted to the Hong Kong people by the central
authorities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
