<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hkhk -Hong Kong-related Data (11): Regional Flag, Emblem of HKSAR </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region, unlike provinces, autonomous regions and
municipalities in China's inland areas, is allowed to have its own
regional flag and emblem.
</P>
<P>
This is a concrete reflection of the principles of "one
country, two systems" and "a high degree of autonomy," and is also
designed to facilitate the external contacts of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
Without the regional flag and emblem, it will be inconvenient
for the SAR to exercise its power, authorized by the Central
Government, to conduct external affairs.
</P>
<P>
The regional flag of the HKSAR is a red flag with a bauhinia in
the center highlighted by five stars-tipped stamens. The red flag
represents the motherland and the white bauhinia represents Hong
Kong, implying that Hong Kong is an inalienable part of China and
prospers in the embrace of the motherland.
</P>
<P>
The five stars in the bauhinia symbolize Hong Kong compatriots'
love of their motherland.
</P>
<P>
The flag and the flower are in different colors, red and white,
symbolizing "one country, two systems."
</P>
<P>
The regional emblem of the HKSAR is round in shape, with its
outer ring carrying the words "Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region of the People's Republic of China" in Chinese and "Hong
Kong" in English.
</P>
<P>
At the center of the emblem is a bauhinia highlighted by five
star-tipped stamens against a red background. The emblem has the
same symbolic meaning as the regional flag.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
