<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Indian Exporters, Industry Favor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Indian exporters and industry
captains are likely to seek a temporary devaluation of the rupee
along with other measures to boost the country's exports when they
meet Prime Minister Inder Kumar Gujral on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is being convened as the initiative of the prime
minister in the wake of poor performance of the export sector last
year and early this fiscal year (April 1997-March 1998).
</P>
<P>
After a growth of over 20 percent in 1995-96, India's exports
grew by only 4.01 percent in 1996-97, according to official
statistics.
</P>
<P>
In April 1997, the first month of the current financial year,
the exports were 10 percent lower than a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
The steady slowdown in export growth has caused widespread
concern in both the Indian government and business circles who are
trying to work out measures to check the decline.
</P>
<P>
President of Federation of Indian Exporters' Organizations
(FIEO) Ramu Deora said a readjustment by 10 percent in the value
of rupee against the U.S. dollar would ensure exports remained
competitive.
</P>
<P>
He said the decline in imports had reduced the demand for
foreign currency. This had raised the value of the rupee against
the dollar, making Indian exports less competitive.
</P>
<P>
A senior industry representative agreed that "a 10-12 percent
devaluation (of rupee) over the next 6-8 months would help."  A
more significant reduction, he added, would lead to retaliatory
action by competing countries.
</P>
<P>
But industry captains are not unanimous over whether
devaluation of the Indian currency is desirable.
</P>
<P>
Some argue that a fall in the value of rupee would push up the
cost of imports and that producers relying on imported inputs
would suffer.
</P>
<P>
Many believe that devaluation would be necessary at least as a
temporary measure before more effective ones to boost exports
could be taken.
</P>
<P>
While in favor of at least a temporary devaluation of the
rupee, Industry captains have urged the Indian government to
improve administration and formulate longer-term measures to boost
exports.
</P>
<P>
In the short term, the Associated Chambers of Commerce and
Industry sources said the government should go in for a 10-12
percent devaluation of the rupee over the next 6-8 months and
bring down the cost of export credit.
</P>
<P>
In the medium term, it should emphasize improving
infrastructures for exports and making Indian products more
competitive globally by reducing taxes on industry.
</P>
<P>
The Indian Customs authorities were also urged to simplify
formalities to improve administration of exports.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970625.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Employers' Group Cautious About Italy's Economic Prospects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Italian employers' organization
Confindustria today said the country's economic prospects in
coming years may not be as bright as the government expects.
</P>
<P>
However, while commenting on a latest government financial
plan, Confindustria said the country may still be able to make way
into the European monetary union before its launch in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The 1998-2000 economic and financial planning document,
submitted by the government in May, passed the Senate floor today
after winning a Chamber of Deputies approval on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Italy's budget deficit this year would be between 3.2-3.6
percent of gross domestic product, or above the 3 percent ceiling
set for the single currency union, Confindustria said.
</P>
<P>
The deficit in 1998 would be 3 percent, still above the
government's target of 2.8 percent, it added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, inflation would be 2.1 percent this year, below the
government's estimate of 2.5 percent, but the unemployment would
be unlikely to go down below 12 percent until 1999.
</P>
<P>
A stagnated economy would be resulted from postponed reform to
improve the quality of public spending, administrative efficiency,
tax system and labor market, said the group.
</P>
<P>
The uncertainties in Italy's public accounts mean that the
country's qualification for joining the European monetary union
will remain a doubt up to May 1998, it said.
</P>
<P>
But "it is reasonably probable that Italy will succeed, albeit
by a hair's breadth, in crossing the line" with some leading
countries into the union, it noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
