<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Nazi Retrialed for Killing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Former Nazi SS captain Erich Priebke
told a military court today that he was forced to take part in
Italy's worst World War Two massacre of 335 men and boys, 75 of
them Jews, at the Ardeatine Caves outside Rome in 1944.
</P>
<P>
Priebke, dressed in a white shirt and grey jacket, read a
prepared statement in Rome's high-security Rebibbia jail where he
is standing trial on charges of complicity in the mass killing.
</P>
<P>
The 83-year-old German said he would have been executed if he
had refused to carry out the order that "came directly from
Hitler".
</P>
<P>
The ex-Nazi officer described his role in carrying out that
terrible order as horrendous thing, a personal tragedy.
</P>
<P>
Priebke returned immediately to the Roman Catholic monastery
south of Rome where he is under house arrest after speaking for
half an hour during his first appearance in the military court
since the retrial opened on April 14.
</P>
<P>
Priebke, who is accused together with former SS major Karl Hass
of complicity in the massacre, was extradited from Argentina in
November 1995.
</P>
<P>
A court found him guilty last August but ruled that he be set
free under a statute of limitation.
</P>
<P>
The retrial was called because the verdict sparked a storm of
protest in Italy and abroad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
