<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gold Dealer Sees Golden Opportunity in Return of HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong gold dealers are
expecting the return of Hong Kong to China on July 1 to bring the
local gold market a new development opportunity that can really be
called a "golden" one.
</P>
<P>
"China has a population of 1.2 billion. If each Chinese buys
one gram of gold, China will consume half of the annual production
of all Western gold mines," Chan Fat Chu, president of the Chinese
Gold and Silver Exchange Society, was quoted as saying by local
media.
</P>
<P>
With its current status as an international financial center,
Hong Kong will serve as a major window for China to purchase
foreign gold, he added.
</P>
<P>
Founded in 1910, the Chinese Gold and Silver Exchange Society
operates one of the largest gold bullion markets in the world.
Gold traded through the society is of 99 percent fineness and
weighted in taels (one tael equals about 1.2 troy ounces).
Turnover on the exchange totaled 15 million taels in 1996.
</P>
<P>
"History has bestowed our society with several major chances of
development, and I believe this year's return is another one,"
Chan said.
</P>
<P>
He said that in the near future, the income of the people in
China's interior areas will increase substantially as a result of
the reform and opening up drive and the influx of foreign
investment.
</P>
<P>
If inflation is under effective control, he said, people will
take out their bank savings and buy gold jewelry as a kind of
investment.
</P>
<P>
"When the sale of gold surges, the People's Bank of China will
need to purchase gold from the international market, and the Hong
Kong gold market will be the best choice," he said.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that the gold jewelry industry in China's interior
areas will enjoy further development in the coming two to three
years, thus promoting the formation of a gold market in the
interior areas that could help set the gold price.
</P>
<P>
He said that it is also necessary for the gold market in the
interior areas to be linked with the Hong Kong gold market to
reduce the risk of a possible collapse caused by any major price
fluctuation in the global market.
</P>
<P>
Noting that there still exist some obstacles, Chan said that
the prospects for the realization of his blueprint are "quite
encouraging."
</P>
<P>
"If we seize this opportunity, our society will be able to
scale a new height," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
