<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Government Cuts Prices of Diesel, Kerosene </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Bowing to mounting pressure, the
Nepali government has decided to lower the prices of diesel and
kerosene, but maintain the price of gas, local press reports said
today.
</P>
<P>
The government has instructed the Nepal Oil Corporation (NOC)
to refix the price of diesel at 15.5 rupees (27 U.S. cents) per
liter, down two rupees, and that of kerosene at 10.5 rupees (18
cents) per liter, down half a rupee, Prime Minister Lokendra
Bahadur Chand said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The gas price will remain unchanged at 39 rupees (68 cents) per
liter, he told a meeting of the Lower House Public Accounts
Committee.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Rabindra Nath Sharma also told the meeting
that the NOC had been directed to fix the price of cooking gas,
another source of concern for the public, at 495 rupees (8.68
dollars) per cylinder.
</P>
<P>
But he said the old stock of liquefied petroleum gas will be
sold at 380 rupees (6.66 dollars) per cylinder for the coming
seven days.
</P>
<P>
The government had agreed to price hikes of petroleum products
in order to reduce the heavy loss the NOC is suffering, said
Chand, adding that the government subsidy has reached 510 million
rupees ((8.95 million dollars) in the past five months alone.
</P>
<P>
However, there have been many complaints from the public since
the new price structure came out on June 12. According to the
price structure, the price of gas would be lifted from 34 rupees
(60 cents) per liter to 39 rupees (68 cents), diesel from 14
rupees (25 cents) to 17.5 rupees (30 cents) and kerosene from 9.5
rupees (17 cents) to 11 rupees (19 cents).
</P>
<P>
Public outrage against petroleum products and cooking gas price
hikes is gaining momentum, with protest movements taking place
now and then, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The major political parties all have voiced their opposition to
the proposed price hikes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
