<HEADLINE> Two Indian Pilots Die as MIG-21s Collide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Two pilots of the Indian Air
Force were killed as the MIG-21 fighters flown by them collided
mid-air over an airbase in India's Assam state on Sunday, The
Indian Express reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to the delayed report, the collision was the first of
its kind in northeastern India.
</P>
<P>
Indian Air Force sources said the aircraft clashed because of
mistiming and the pilots failed to bail out due to low altitude of
the flight.
</P>
<P>
The Air force authorities had reportedly removed the wreckage
of the aircraft on Monday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
