<HEADLINE> Gebrselassie Eyes World Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian 5,000 meters world record
holder Haile Gebrselassie said here on Tuesday he would decide
about competing in August's world championships after trying to
reclaim the 10,000 meters world record.
</P>
<P>
The 24-year-old Gebrselassie, who won Olympic gold at 10,000m
last year, said it was more important personally to break Moroccan
Salah Hissou's record of 26 minute 38.08 seconds than to go to
Athens.
</P>
<P>
Gebrselassie voiced his ambition at the news conference before
Wednesday's Paris Grand Prix Athletics Meeting, which was shiny
owing to some hottest names in the international athletic arena.
</P>
<P>
Among those track and field big guns, double Olympic champion
Michael Johnson noted at the conference that he was just focussing
on his race in Paris, not considering for the moment whether he
could obtain a possible wild card entry for August's world
championship in Athens.
</P>
<P>
Johnson, unable to run in the American trials because of a
strained quadricep muscle suffered in his 150 meters duel with
Canadian 100 meters world record holder Dovovan Bailey, also
shrugged off the questions from reporters whether he had ever
taken drugs.
</P>
<P>
Denmark's Kenyan-born 800 meters world champion Wilson Kipketer
would not tell how he had been preparing for the Paris Meeting but
assured that he would give all of himself to hit top.
</P>
<P>
The home favourite, double Olympic gold medalist Marie-Jose
Perec did not offer goals for the Paris Meeting. The Frenwoman
claimed she had been out of training for an entire week and was
still feeling uncomfortable with her legs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
