<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Sets Limits on Petrochemical Plants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 25 (Xinhua) -- In a bid to strengthen macro
management of the petrochemical sector, China will restrict the
construction of the new ethylene production and oil refining
projects in the remaining years of the century, today's "China
Daily" reports.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing-based newspaper quotes Ma Chengquan, a senior
official with the State Planning Commission, as saying that China
will improve and expand existing refineries instead of setting up
new crude oil processing firms.
</P>
<P>
The current refineries and refineries under construction will
be capable of processing enough crude oil by 2000. The government
will take measures to improve its refineries, so they can increase
their capability of processing imported crude oil.
</P>
<P>
The government will launch an overhaul of existing crude oil
processing units, and will issue licenses to qualified processing
units after the overhaul.
</P>
<P>
Ma also said that China is unavoidable to increase imports of
crude oil because domestic oil production is hard to meet the
needs of the country's economic development.
</P>
<P>
China will not approve new ethylene production projects before
2000 except for those foreign funded projects already
approved. Three of four large petrochemical bases capable of
producing at least one million tons of ethylene will be formed by
2010. 
</P>
</TEXT>
