<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profile: Haixia Brings Aurae to WNBA (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 25 (Xinhua) -- At 30 years of age, playing for
the Los Angeles Sparks in the WNBA's inaugural season is a tough
challenge for China's towering center, Zheng Haixia. But she loves
to face it.
</P>
<P>
"It's my long-time dream to play abroad with great world
stars," said Haixia, who bears the tag of "Great Wall of China" by
Australian coach Robyn Maher during the World Women's Basketball
Championship in Sydney in 1994.
</P>
<P>
"I'm excited to play in the new professional league, in which
many of the best players around the world have joined, and I am
confident that players from China are qualified," she said prior
to her departure for Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
The eight-team league made its debut last Saturday when Haixia
scored eigh points and grabbed five rebounds in her 18-minute
play. Unfortunately, her host Sparks lost to Charlotte Sting 57-67.
</P>
<P>
"All of us were disappointed at the defeat," Haixia said. "I
didn't play my game as in my home because I was too eager to show
well. It's a hard lession and I am sure I can play better later."
</P>
<P>
A 6-8 center and four-time Olympian, Haixia is not a stranger
to the fans in the United States, because of her outings to both
the Los Angeles and Atlanta Olympics and her pivotal role for the
Chinese national squad.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, Haixia paced China to a silver medal at the World
Women's Basketball Championship with 26.3 points and 13.4 rebounds
per game. Voted MVP at the tournament, Haixia says it was the best
she's ever played.
</P>
<P>
Four months later, however, the same team was outscored 30
points by South Korea in the Hiroshima Asian Games, and China
failed to enter the Asian finals for the first time in twenty
years.
</P>
<P>
Haixia felt humiliated although she remained as top scorer of
19 points for the team.
</P>
<P>
During the Asian Games, the towering center shot a miserable 44
percent from the field and 56 percent from the free throw line,
against her 83 and 84 percent marks in Australia.
</P>
<P>
"It was a terrible game -- a disaster," she said. "I couldn't
believe it. Our defense was so poor that South Korea even scored
103 points with 10 three-pointers. They had never done that
against us."
</P>
<P>
Born in a peasant family in central Henan Province, Haixia
began her basketball career with a local sports academy when she
was 12 years old and already 5-10. Three years later, she grew to
over 6-7 and was drafted by the Wuhan Army club. In 1982, Haixia
joined in the Chinese youth team which won the Asian championship
and made her senior national debut the folllowing season.
</P>
<P>
"Eager to learn on and off the court, she had made great
strides in her first year in the national team," said Yang Boyong,
then national coach.
</P>
<P>
In 1984, Haixia, at the age of 17, shot 59 percent from the
field as China finished third in the Los Angeles Olympics. "I was
the youngest of the team when I first took part in the Olympics,"
Haixia recalled.
</P>
<P>
She has since played in three more Olympics and four World
Championships, and China has become a fearsome squad in the world
from the moment Haixia started her national caps. She once scored
67 points in a friendly against a Soviet club.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970625.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profile: Haixia Brings Aurae to WNBA (2-last) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In 1990, Haixia was nagged by a back injury and she barely
managed 10 minutes on court two years later when China finished
runners-up in the Barcelona Olympics. Back home, she vowed to lose
weight and get in shape.
</P>
<P>
"Both her weaks and the successes of her teammates in Barcelona
became catalyst for Haixia to work even hard for the Sydney world
championship," said coach Chen Daohong, who stepped off from the
post after Atlanta. "She needed to prove herself to the world and
resumed training even when she was undergoing medical treatment."
</P>
<P>
Haixia weighted 30 pounds lighter when the 1994 Worlds came
around and the effect was almost magical.
</P>
<P>
"Her play and conditioning has improved tremendously," said USA
head coach Tara VanDerveer. "She is just so much bigger than
everybody else. She clogs up the passing lanes and presents all
kind of problems. If she weren't so big, she wouldn't be a
problem."
</P>
<P>
After the triumph in Australia, Haixia headed the Chinese team
to take the bronze medal in the Goodwill Games in St Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
Yet, her back injury was flaring up and she could train only
sporadically prior to the Asian Games. But she was not to give
up. "As long as the team needs me, I'll be there," said Haixia, "I
want to be there for revenge against South Korea in the 1995 Asian
Championship and to take part in the 1996 Olympics."
</P>
<P>
And the moment came in July 1995 when Haixia and her teammates
defeated South Koreans 94-69 in the Asian Championship. Haixia won
the honour of MVP.
</P>
<P>
In Atlanta, she suffered another big blow when China failed to
enter the last eight with one win against four defeats in the
preliminaries, including a 72-75 loss to Japan, through she scored
a game-high 31 points.
</P>
<P>
"It's disappointing for us in Atlanta," said Haixia who
averaged 18.1 points per game as her team finished ninth place,
the worst record for the Chinese women cagers in the Olympic
history.
</P>
<P>
However, the setback couldn't keep Haixia offhands from the
sport she loved so much. After Atlanta she led the August First
club to retain the Women's National League title last October.
</P>
<P>
As Haixia was abroad for WNBA, China has no alternative for her
post, but it still has the merits to both Haixia herself and the
development of the Chinese women basketball, said Zhong Tianfa,
vice president of the Chinese Basketball Association.
</P>
<P>
"Her departure didn't mean she will never represent China
again. Should she keep her form, she could still be in our
national squad, including the year of 2000," Zhong said.
</P>
<P>
"To play the 2000 Olympic Games? Then I'll be 33 years old,"
Haixia said to Xinhua last summer. "It'll be too hard for me
because I'll be too old."
</P>
<P>
If Haixia continues to play to her usual high level, don't be
surprised shen she turns up in the Sydney Olympics representing
China once again. 
</P>
</TEXT>
