<HEADLINE> Venezuelan President Stresses Military Role </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Venezuelan President Rafael
Caldera today underlined the military role in defending the
country's sovereignty in face of the persistent incursions of the
Colombian guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
The armed forces have assumed a new and demanding
responsibility in face of the threat of "regular forces that are
acting in the neighboring country," Caldera said at a
celebration ceremony of the Army Day and 176th anniversary of
Venezuela's independence.
</P>
<P>
The president, also commander-in-chief of the armed forces,
pointed out that the military contributes to the strengthening of
democratic order in the country.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony was held in the northern city of Carabobo, where
the critical Battle of Carabobo was fought 176 years ago to free
the country from Spanish dominion.
</P>
<P>
At the ceremony, about 6,000 soldiers belonging to 35 army
units participated in a military parade, several of whom just
completed missions in the areas along the Venezuelan-Colombian
border.
</P>
<P>
Senior officials, including Defense Minister Pedro Nicolas
Valencia Vivas, President of the National Congress Cristobal
Fernandez, also attended the ceremony. 
</P>
</TEXT>
