<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Become Asia's Main Pulp Producer in 2003 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia is expected to become
the biggest pulp producer in the Asian region in the year 2003
owing to good prospects, increasing production and installed
capacity of national industry, an official report said.
</P>
<P>
A report issued Tuesday by the Ministry of Industry and Trade
said that with a production capacity of 2.266 million tons per
year in 1996, Indonesia was ranked 12th among 23 pulp producing
countries.
</P>
<P>
It is predicted that by the end of the seventh five-year
development plan (1999-2004), Indonesia's installed pulp
production capacity will reach 10.3 million tons a year.
</P>
<P>
There are now 16 pulp producing plants in Indonesia with a
combined production capacity of 3.348 million tons and 74 paper
plants with a capacity of 7.242 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's five main pulp export destination countries in 1996
were South Korea, China, Italy, Japan and India.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
