<HEADLINE> Bosnian Croatian Officer Put on Trial in Hague </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, June 24 (Xinhua) -- A Bosnian ethnic Croatian
officer, who was indicted for war crimes, went on trial in the
International Court of Justice in The Hague on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Tihomir Blaskic, 36, is the first officer brought to trial on
charge of war crimes in the former Yugoslavia, the Yugoslav news
agency Tanjug reported from The Hague,
</P>
<P>
He was charged with killing muslim civilians during ethnic
cleansing of Lasva valley area in central Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Blaskic was detained in a secret place before he was sent to
The Hague in April 1996.
</P>
<P>
The International Criminal Tribunal for the Former Yugoslavia,
which was founded in The Hague in November 1993 under United
Nations Security Council resolutions, is entitled to handle
trials on those who have seriously violated humanitarian laws
since 1991 in the former Yugoslavia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
