<HEADLINE> Italy Urges Slovenia, Romania's Entry into NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi
strongly renewed his country's support today for the early entry
of Slovenia and Romania into the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
"I firmly back the proposal to bring Slovenia and Romania into
the NATO's planned expansion," he said in an interview with CNN
television.
</P>
<P>
The reasons for admitting the two nations are very simple
because the southeastern part of Europe will become the most
complicated and volatile region in the continent, both politically
and economically, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Italian prime minister said at the closing ceremony of the
Denver summit that United States President Bill Clinton's refusal
to support the two nations' access to NATO was a serious mistake.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has claimed that only Poland, Hungary and the Czech
Republic should be in NATO's first wave of enlargement.
</P>
<P>
However, Italy, France and other European nations also support
granting NATO membership to Slovenia and Romania as Slovenia, a
Balkan state, plays a crucial strategic military role in
connecting Hungary to other members of the alliance, while
Romania, which borders the Black Sea, would provide a needed
equilibrium in NATO's south. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
