<HEADLINE> Iran Demands OPEC Measures to Stop Oil Overproduction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Oil Minister Gholamreza
Aghazadeh urged the Organization of the Petroleum Exporting
Countries (OPEC) today to take steps to prevent its members from
pumping oil above official ceiling and guarantee crude oil price
stability.
</P>
<P>
On the eve of OPEC regular meeting on Wednesday, Aghazadeh told
reporters here that he was dissatisfied with the current oil prices
that had dropped sharply since January and urged OPEC to stop
the trend. Oil prices depended on actions OPEC took in the market,
he said.
</P>
<P>
OPEC sets the production ceiling for its members at 25.03
million barrels daily, but the real output is some 2 million
beyond.
</P>
<P>
Oil prices have plunged from 23 U.S. dollars a barrel by 1996's
end to the current level of about 17 dollars, well below OPEC's
target of 21 dollars.
</P>
<P>
However, local experts suggest oil prices will continue to be
weak in the international market whatever the results the regular
meeting would achieve, because oil reserves have risen quickly
worldwide making OPEC members less competitive with the non-OPEC
members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
