<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Senate Approves Government's Financial Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The Italian Senate today endorsed a
government plan to bring down budgetary deficit to within three
percent of gross domestic product by the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The upper house of parliament's endorsement came in its
approval of the government's 1998-2000 economic and financial
plan, which sets binding objectives for trimming the deficit.
</P>
<P>
As a key part of the document, the lower deficit would keep
Italy in line with a crucial parameter of the Maastricht treaty
for entry into the European single currency set to launch in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The government plan calls for cutting the deficit by at least
25 trillion lire (about 15 billion U.S. dollars) in two years.
</P>
<P>
Of the total, 10 trillion lire (6 billion dollars) would be
made up by new taxes and revenues and the remaining 15 trillion
lire (9 billion dollars) by savings from government spending.
</P>
<P>
The planning document, submitted by the government in May,
passed the Chamber of Deputies, or the lower house of parliament,
on Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
