<DOCNO> XIE19970625.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A Golden Waterway to HK (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The Zhujiang River, or Pearl
River, the second largest after the Yangtze River in terms of
surface flow, has become China's busiest "golden waterway" to
expand trade between Hong Kong and the inland areas.
</P>
<P>
The river flows through Yunnan Province, the Guangxi Zhuang
Autonomous Region and Guangdong Province in southwest and south
China and empties into the South China Sea via Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
A dozen cargo ships carry foods, such as fresh vegetables,
fruit, fish, and fowls, to Hong Kong each morning from Guangzhou,
capital of Guangdong. Sources say that the amount of food going to
Hong Kong reaches 50,000 tons a month.
</P>
<P>
More than 200 river ports are scattered in the Zhujiang river
delta, where the speed of construction of such facilities comes
first in China. So far, more than 20 large and medium-sized ports
have been or are being built along the river in the Guangzhou,
Zhuhai and Shenzhen areas, where the density of river ports is the
highest in southern China.
</P>
<P>
Ten thousand-ton vessels can sail from Hong Kong to Guangzhou
and 1,000-ton ships to Zhaoqing in Guangdong and Wuzhou, Guiping,
and Guigang in Guangxi; small boats of 300 to 500 tons can get to
the upper reaches of the Zhujiang river system.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the Zhujiang Shipping Administration of the
Ministry of Communications show that more than 2,300 large vessels
ply between Hong Kong and the inland areas each day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970625.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. House Votes to End Bosnia Operations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The United States House of
Representatives today, in a 278-148 vote, called for an end of
funding to U.S. military operations in Bosnia after June 30, 1998,
though the Pentagon opposes this strongly.
</P>
<P>
The date to end U.S. participation in the U.N. peacekeeping
mission was agreed by President Bill Clinton. But the Defense
Department fears that a mandatory withdrawal date would put
U.S. troops in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
Franklin Raines, director of the White House Office of
Management and Budget, said administration officials will
recommend the president veto the 1998 defense authorization bill
if the Bosnia withdrawal amendment is included in the final
version.
</P>
<P>
The Senate is expected to vote on its version of the 268.2
billion U.S. dollar defense bill next month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
