<DOCNO> XIE19970625.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A Golden Waterway to HK (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Authorities point out that the tremendous amount of cargo
moving along the Zhujiang has led to its boom. Statistics show
that Guangdong now has 490,000 Hong Kong-funded enterprises which
have moved their factories to the interior and marketed their
products overseas.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, large quantities of goods from Hunan, Guizhou,
and Guangxi have also been shipped along the Zhujiang to Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The number of ships going to Hong Kong along the Zhujiang
reached 112,000 in 1996, handling more than 38 million tons of
cargo and accounting for one-eighth of Hong Kong's total handling
capacity, according to statistics from Hong Kong's Port
Development Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Container transport has been increasing at an annual rate of 35
percent in recent years on the Zhujiang. Now six of every ten
containers handled by Hong Kong are shipped by the Zhujiang either
way.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ninth Five-Year Plan (1996-2000) of the
Guangdong Provincial Communications Department, nearly a billion
yuan will be invested in expanding and upgrading inland river
ports, in a bid to further tap the Zhujiang's potentiality.
</P>
<P>
Economists note that the further development of the river's
transport will enable Hong Kong to push its economic growth
northward into the inland areas of south China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970625.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
