<HEADLINE> Panama To Build Naval Base To Control Coasts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Panama will build a naval
surveillance base in the near future in the western province of
Chiriqui to fight drug trafficking, poaching and other illegal
activities carried out along its border with Costa Rica, said
National Maritime Service (SMN) spokesperson today.
</P>
<P>
The two-hectare Quebrada de Piedra Base, 97 miles from the
Costa Rican border will have a heliport, floating dock,
intercommunication tower, hangars, fuel tank and water deposits.
</P>
<P>
The 25-unit security force and two patrol units equipped with
speedboats, will begin operations at the end of this year help
lower the incidence of illegal activities that use Panamanian
coasts as a pathway to Central and South America.
</P>
<P>
The SMN expects to incorporate new recruits to the current
contingent of 446 seamen.
</P>
<P>
The SMN will also complement the surveillance work in other
Pacific-sector bases, including the bases in the provinces of
Veraguas, Chiriqui, Panama and Darien. 
</P>
</TEXT>
