<DOCNO> XIE19970625.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seminar Reviews Role of Foreign Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Senior trade officials and
researchers called for fair treatment of transnationals which
bring both pluses and minuses to the Chinese economy, according to
today's "China Daily".
</P>
<P>
While transnational companies have channeled in money China
badly needs, they have also sometimes backed domestic firms into a
corner.
</P>
<P>
The advantage of transnationals holding majority shares in
joint ventures lies in their willingness to transfer advanced
technology and sufficient capital to China, delegates to a Beijing
seminar agreed.
</P>
<P>
But some feared powerful foreign investors would crush domestic
industries.
</P>
<P>
The seminar was held against a recent drop in overall foreign
investment in China, prompting nationwide debate on how best to
court foreign money.
</P>
<P>
Transnational are understood to have bucked the declining trend
of foreign investment because - backed by strong financial power -
they are less liable to China's tariffs that tend to affect
smaller foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
There have been worries among some Chinese that the national
interest and economic sovereignty would be at stake if
transnationals control business in more sectors.
</P>
<P>
"If does not matter who is the big boss. What we need is our
own growth," said a company manager.
</P>
<P>
But is was agreed that an anti-monopoly law should come out as
soon as possible to prevent transnationals from cornering a
certain industry.
</P>
<P>
Delegates also urged the State to publicize investment guides
telling transnationals where they can or cannot hold a major
stake.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
