<DOCNO> XIE19970625.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taliban Reject G8 Plea for Broad-based Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan Islamic Taliban
militia have rejected a call by leading industrialized countries
for a broad-based government, reports reaching here said today.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban, with two-thirds of Afghanistan under their
control, was inclusive enough to satisfy all Afghans, the
Taliban's "Deputy Minister for Information and Culture" Abdul
Rahman Hotaki was quoted as saying Tuesday in Kabul.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban, who captured the capital Kabul last September,
would set about consolidating their administration on their own
terms, Hotaki said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on behalf of G8 members following a summit meeting in
Denver, U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright Sunday called
on the Afghan warring factions to stop fighting and form a
broad-based government.
</P>
<P>
The G8, which includes Group of Seven (G7) members of Britain,
Canada, France, Germany, Italy, Japan and the United States, plus
Russia, also told the warring factions that the U.N. peace talks
were the best avenue for ending their 18-year-old civil war.
</P>
</TEXT>
