<HEADLINE> Brief Latin American Economic News (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The following are the major
economic news briefs from latin American countries over the past
few days:
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- In face of an imminent free trade agreement
between El Salvador and Guatemala, the Nicaraguan government
undertook measures to establish an agreement with similar
conditions with Honduras, revealed Nicaraguan Economy Ministry
authorities.
</P>
<P>
Nicaragua is keeping a close watch on the free trade agreement
between both neighboring countries, according to the sources.
Nicaraguan Economy Minister Noel Sacasa visited Honduras last week
to study a plan that will enable them to work in the same
direction.
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- Costa Rica's budget deficit decreased 13 percent
during the first five months of this year compared with the same
period in 1996, according to Finance Ministry statistics.
</P>
<P>
Between January-May, the budget deficit totaled 170 million
dollars compared with 148.5 million dollars for the same period
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Total spending by the Costa Rican government during the first
5 months of this year reached 681 million dollars while its
revenues were 511 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- During January-May, Mexico had a trade surplus
of 1.652 billion dollars, said the Ministry of Finance and
Public Credit.
</P>
<P>
The surplus resulted from 42.965 billion dollars worth of
exports versus 41.313 billion dollars worth of imports.
</P>
<P>
Overseas sales increased 13.6 percent while foreign purchases
increased 19.8 percent with respect to the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Agrium, a Canadian fertilizer company, decided
to invest 600 million dollars in the building of an urea plant in
Argentina.
</P>
<P>
Agrium will carry out its project together with the state-owned
oil company Yacimientos Petroliferos Fiscales and the Perez Compac
company.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian company expects to invest another 10 million
dollars to build a lime pellet factory in Argentina. (to be
continued)


nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
