<HEADLINE> Brief Latin American Economic News (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS -- Venezuelan exports of crude oil and refined
products reached 5.1 billion dollars during the first four months
of this year, said PDVSA, Venezuela'S state-owned oil company.
</P>
<P>
The high level of revenues was attributed to the prices
obtained by PDVSA's affiliated operators: Lagoven, Corpoven and
Maraven.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Automobile sales totaled 65,162 units during the
first five months of this year in Chile, an increase of 1.6
percent over the same period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Chevrolet Company headed sales with 7,905 units,
including freight trucks, followed by Japan's Nissan with 7,480
units and South Korea's Hyundai with 7,102 units.
</P>
<P>
Chevrolet had a 12.43 percent share of the market, Nissan 11.48
and Hyundai 10.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- The production of textiles, garments and
leather goods in Uruguay increased 7.6 percent during the first
quarter of this year compared with the same period in 1996, said
the National Statistics Institute.
</P>
<P>
The subsection, "stockings and knits", headed growth with
19.5 percent during the period analyzed, followed by "apparel"
with 12.7 percent, "washing, spinning and knitting" 8 percent
and "tanning and finishing workshops" 5.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- The industrial sector will be the recipient of 54
percent of the foreign investments that will reach a total of 107
billion dollars in Brazil by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The automobile sector will report 7.7 billion dollars of
foreign capital by that date, according to experts. (to be
continued)


nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
