<HEADLINE> Brief Latin American Economic News (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- Panamanian authorities will privatize two sugar
mills through public auctions this November, said Horacio
Rodriguez, managers of the La Victoria Calv Sugar Company.
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- Rodrigo Bolanos, the president of Costa Rica's
central bank said that there is a good possibility that the
country will have an economic growth of 2.5 percent of its gross
domestic product and less than 12 percent of inflation.
</P>
<P>
This panorama could result in lower interest rates that would
contribute to a reactivation of the economy, pointed out
Bolanos.
</P>
<P>
The monthly index of economic activity, which used to measure
the country's economy, has been showing a gradual increase for the
past six months, he added.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Foreign financial investments in Argentina
reached 21.503 billion dollars in May, an increase of 74.7
percent over the same month in 1996, said the National
Securities Commission.
</P>
<P>
Belgium was the main source of the foreign financial
investments with 7.06515 billion dollars which represented 32.86
percent of the total, pointed out a commission report.
</P>
<P>
The United States was second with 7.01558 billion dollars.
</P>
