<DOCNO> XIE19970625.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dam to Help Tame Capricious Waterway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The Yellow River will be tamed
when a major dam is built across its troublesome middle reaches,
today's "China Daily" reports.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing-based English newspaper quotes Zhang Jiyao,
vice-minister of water resources who is in charge of the project
as saying that the Xiaolangdi Dam, getting its name for nearing a
village known as Xiaolangdi, about 40 kilometers north of Luoyang,
in central China's Henan province, is set for completion on
October 31 as construction work accelerates with international
assistance.
</P>
<P>
As the largest project of its kind on the Yellow River,
Xiaolangdi Dam is estimated to cost 4.5 million US dollars with
about 1.2 billion US dollars in loan from the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
When completed, the project will enable the river to withstand
the once-in-1,000-year flood, and it will also solve the river's
ice floods in early spring, with its reservoir designed to
minimize heavy silt build-up, irrigate farmland with four billion
cubic meters of water each year and generate electricity.
</P>
<P>
The project is one of the most challenging in dam-building
history because of the complex geological structure of the site,
its large scale, engineering difficulties and about 200,000 local
people who have to be relocated, the paper says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970625.0292 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cape Town Seeks Asian Votes in Olympic Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Cape Town is making big
efforts to win the Asian vote in order to secure the right to host
the 2004 Olympic games.
</P>
<P>
Ntsundeni Madzunya, director of international affair of the
Cape Town Bid Company, said on Tuesday that Asia would be crucial
to the city's chances.
</P>
<P>
"We hope the base of Cape Town's support and the core of it
will come from Africa and Asia," he said on his return from a
six-nation tour of Asia.
</P>
<P>
During his tour, Madzunya had held talks with six Asian members
in the International Olympic Committee and will visit both Koreas,
China and Japan at the start of July.
</P>
<P>
Cape Town officials expect to have met all 18 IOC members from
Asia by the end of July.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, an independent survey indicated that the majority of
South African whites oppose government spending on Cape Town's bid
for the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
The survey said blacks and Asians polled were most supportive
with 74 per cent and 75 per cent respectively supporting
government involvement.
</P>
<P>
However, among the country's minority white population only 47
per cent supported the idea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
