<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Second Seed Chang Crashed out of Wimbledon Championships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WIMBLEDON, June 24 (Xinhua) -- World number two Michael Chang
of the United States crashed out of the Wimbledon Open Tennis
Championshiops Tuesday evening after losing a five-set battle to
Todd Woodbridge of Australia 6-7, 6-3, 2-6, 6-3, 6-8.
</P>
<P>
Chang, who was also downed by a Spanish player at the first
round of 1996 Wimbledon Championships, put up an extraordinary
fightback after losing first two sets, but the fifth seed was
unable to turn the tables around at the final set.
</P>
<P>
With Chang's victorious opponent rating the match as the
biggest win of his career, the American Chinese was obviously
unhappy, saying "it's a little disappointing, but I have the rest
of the season to look forward to."
</P>
<P>
Another major seeded casualty is Brzalian Gustavo Kuerton. The
new French Open champion also lost a five-set battle to Justin
Gimelstob of the United States 3-6, 4-6, 6-4, 6-1, 4-6.
</P>
<P>
Seventh seed Mark Philippoussis of Austrialia, one of the most
powerful servers in the world, was also defeated by Britain's
non-seeded player Greg Rusedski 6-7, 6-7, 3-6.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, world number one Pete Sampras, Boris Becker of
Germany, Russian Yevgeny Kafelnikov and other major seeds also
ousted their opponents in straight sets.
</P>
<P>
In the women's events, world number one Martina Hingsi of
Switzerland enjoyed a smooth sailing into the second round by
defeating Anne Kremer of Luxembourg in straight sets 6-4, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
Despite of fierce resistance from her strong opponent, the
16-year-old Hingis, also the women's top seed, played some
astonishing tennis and finally snatched the first victory.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, eighth seed Arantxa Sanchez Vicarrio of Spain, Ank
Huber of Germay and 10th seed Conchita Martinez also entered the
next round. 
</P>
</TEXT>
