<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Small Island States Urges Actions Against Global </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Fearing of submersion,
small island states today called for actions against global
warming in the general debate at the 19th Special Session of the
General Assembly, which was opened Monday.
</P>
<P>
These nations, including Cyprus, Caribbean nations and Pacific
archipelagos, said their survival was threatened by the rise of
sea level, resulting from growing emission of carbon dioxide and
other greenhouse gases.
</P>
<P>
President Maumoon Abdul Gayoom of Maldives said that "80
percent of low-lying islands such as those of the Maldives and
many in the Pacific Ocean would be totally submerged" if global
warming was not curbed.
</P>
<P>
"The process may be too gradual to make sensational headlines,
but the threat, nevertheless, would be no less real," he said.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, President Jacob Nena of the Pacific Micronesia chain
said rising sea levels and more frequent storms had wiped out food
sources and some smaller atolls had already had to be abandoned.
</P>
<P>
"Help us, help all of us, including yourselves, to see that the
legacy of Rio is not lost," he said.
</P>
<P>
The representative of Papua New Guinea, Ututa U. Samana said
his country was concerned by the lack of progress on climate
change. Activities threating the global atmosphere and contributed
to dangerous rises in sea levels threatened the existence of
people throughout the world, he added.
</P>
<P>
Governments are negotiating a treaty to cut back greenhouse
gases. The Europeans have set specific goals but neither the
United States, Canada nor Japan have agreed to their targets of
reducing emissions by 15 percent below the 1990 levels by 2010.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
