<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Praises House Approval of MFN for China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 24 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today praised the House of Representatives for backing his
decision to extend the MFN trade status for China.
</P>
<P>
The House of Representatives this afternoon voted 259 to 173 to
turn down a bill, staged by Republican Representative Gerald
Solomon, of disapproving Clinton's decision.
</P>
<P>
"Today's vote was a vote for America's interests," Clinton said
in a statement issued by the White House.
</P>
<P>
"It sends a clear signal to our friends and foes alike that
when it comes to America's security and prosperity, our nation
speaks with one voice," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the U.S. Chamber of Commerce hailed the House's
approval for China's MFN status.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. Chamber of Commerce thanked the 259 members of the
House of Representatives who voted today to grant Most Favored
Nation status to China as critical to maintaining normal trade
relations with the world's most populous nation," John Howard,
Chamber director of international policy and programs, said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
The U.S Chamber of Commerce has been a strong supporter for
permanent MFN status for China as a means to avoid the wrenching
annual debates, and again called for granting a permanent status.
</P>
<P>
"This annual review harms our credibility, costs us business
and helps our competitors," said Howard. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970625.0305 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Approves MFN for China With Healthy Majority </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The House of Representatives
today rejected an attempt to overrule a decision made by President
Bill Clinton to extend the Most Favored Nation (MFN) trade status
for China, and approved to maintain the normal trade relations
between the United States and China.
</P>
<P>
The result came after Representatives turned down with a
healthy majority of 259-173 a bill, staged by Republican
Representative Gerald Solomon, of disapproving President Clinton's
decision.
</P>
<P>
Supporters for the normal trade relations between the United
States and China believed revocation of China's MFN could simply
deal damaging blows to the Sino-U.S. relations and affect greatly
U.S. strategic interests in the Asian Pacific region as well as
U.S. economic interests as the Sino-U.S. trade provides a great
amount of opportunities of jobs and cheap consumer goods for
Americans.
</P>
<P>
Last year supporters of MFN, a misnomer for normal trade
relations enjoyed by almost every U.S. trading partner, won easily
286 to 141.
</P>
<P>
Democratic Representative Charles Rangel said he believed the
result of the vote could continue the dialogue between the two
countries and create jobs for the United States.
</P>
<P>
Supporters of Clinton's decision of renewal of China's MFN also
said that cutting off normal trade ties would end up backfiring on
the United States and hurt Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
House Ways and Means trade subcommittee Chairman Philip Crane,
a Republican representative, said 50 percent of China's exports to
the United States and 49 percent of U.S. exports to China flow
through Hong Kong which is to return to China on July 1.
</P>
<P>
"Denying MFN to China would threaten 70,000 jobs in Hong Hong,"
Crane said.
</P>
<P>
The White House got a boost in its defense of normal trade with
China on the eve of the House's debate over China's MFN when three
former presidents, six former secretaries of state and 10 former
defense secretaries wrote letters saying withholding normal trade
relations with China was the wrong way to go. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970625.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: North Urged to Fulfill Commitment to Agenda 21 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNINTED NATIONS, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Though the concept of
sustainable development had now been accepted worldwide, efforts
of developing countries to implement Agenda 21 had continued to be
hampered by lack of resources, the 19th special session of the
General Assembly was told today.
</P>
<P>
Ricardo Alarcon de Quesada, president of the National Assembly
of Cuba, urged the North countries to pay their ecological debt
since their irrational consumption patterns were responsible for
the environment's deterioration. They should not only change those
patterns but also transfer to the underdeveloped nations
environmentally rational technologies in the preferential terms
defined at Rio. Instead, the developed countries were trying to
change their Rios commitments and to set arbitrary restrictions
that would make sustainable development more difficult for the
underdeveloped world.
</P>
<P>
He said that the world's poor had multiplied and become poorer
since the 1992 Rio Conference. There were 358 people in the world
whose assets exceed the combined annual income of states inhabited
by 2.5 billion people, some 45 percent of the world's population.
Official development assistance (ODA) had dropped to 1983 levels
while the debt service of third world countries was more than
three times ODA.
</P>
<P>
Gonzalo Sanchez de Lozada, president of Bolivia, said that
developing countries were striving to eradicate poverty and
developed countries wished to prevent a repetition of mistakes
made. Differences between members of the international community
did not justify the lack of progress since Rio.
</P>
<P>
Economic development must be combined with social development
and environmental protection. It was a shared responsibility. The
international community must demonstrate pro-active solidarity.
Resources from official development assistance must be increased
and utilized appropriately for the well-being of all people, he
stressed.
</P>
<P>
Ohn Gyaw, minister for foreign affairs of Myanmar, said that
the last five years had made it clear that sustainable development
programs had inflicted considerable burdens on the developing
countries. It was sad that many developing countries were faced
with a declining volume of official development assistance and it
was crucial that the developed countries reaffirm their
commitments.
</P>
<P>
Maumoon Abdul Gayoom, president of Maldives, stressed that
global climate change was a very real threat to small island
states. The Barbados conference on small island developing states
was an important follow-up to Agenda 21. But nothing had been
achieved since that conference in the way of additional resource
mobilization, technology transfer and capacity-building for
sustainable development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970625.0307 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Hails Holbrooke's Statements on Cyprus as </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The Greek government today hailed
the statements by U.S. special presidential envoy on the Cyprus
issue Richard Holbrooke as positive.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke said Monday that he firmly opposed linking the Cyprus
problem with Greek-Turkish relations, especially concerning the
Aegean. The Cyprus issue should be resolved within the framework
of a single sovereign state, he added.
</P>
<P>
The solution of a single sovereignty in the framework of a
bi-zonal and bi-communal federation seemed unavoidable, he said.
</P>
<P>
Greek government spokesman Dimitris Reppas said today that the
U.S. envoy seemed to want to deal in "a systematic and diligent
way" with efforts to find a solution to the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, Athens would wait for him to undertake the
initiative and should judge him in practice.
</P>
<P>
The government believed that Holbrooke's initiative would be
manifested after quite some time, possibly following forthcoming
direct talks between Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides and Turkish
Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash and elections in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since Turkey "invaded" in 1974
following a Greek-engineered coup on the island.
</P>
<P>
Clerides and Denktash will meet on July 9 in New York for
U.N.-sponsored talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970625.0308 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Bounces Back </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Stocks on Wall Street rallied
back today, adding more than 150 points to the Dow Jones
industrial average, as investors made a buying opportunity of
Monday's steep selloff.
</P>
<P>
The Dow recouped 153.80 points to 7,758.06. The blue chip gauge
plummeted 192 points Monday.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 9-to-5 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with the volume reaching 542.65
million shares, up from 492.70 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list rose 17.72 to 896.34, and
the NYSE composite index rose 7.68 to 466.17, leaving both
measures less than 2 points shy of record territory.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index rose 18.11 points to 1,452.43,
beating last Thursday's record finish at 1,447.14.
</P>
<P>
But the American Stock Exchange composite index fell 0.56 to
619.86.
</P>
<P>
Stocks had started the session strong as investors decided that
the previous day's selloff was an overreaction to a perceived
threat by Japan to dump U.S. bonds.
</P>
<P>
Higher consumer confidence suggests increased spending, which
could aggravate inflationary pressures at the nation's busy
factories. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
