<DOCNO> XIE19970625.0309 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Chamber of Commerce Hails House Approval of China MFN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Chamber of Commerce
today welcomed a majority of House representatives endorsing
continued trade relations with China by rejecting an attempt to
overturn President Bill Clinton's decision for the renewal of MFN
for China.
</P>
<P>
The House of Representatives this afternoon voted 259 to 173 to
turn down a bill, staged by Republican Representative Gerald
Solomon, of disapproving Clinton's decision.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Chamber of Commerce thanked the 259 members of the
House of Representatives who voted today to grant Most Favored
Nation status to China as critical to maintaining normal trade
relations with the world's most populous nation.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Chamber of Commerce has been a strong supporter for
permanent MFN status for China as a means to avoid the wrenching
annual debates, and again called for granting a permanent status.
</P>
<P>
"This annual review harms our credibility, costs us business
and helps our competitors," said John Howard, Chamber director of
international policy and programs.
</P>
<P>
"American companies exported nearly 12 billion dollars worth of
products to China last year," he said. "This supported at least
170,000 high-wage American jobs. And the World Bank estimated that
China must invest 746 billion dollars in infrastructure
development over the next decade -- a potentially huge market for
U.S. products and services."
</P>
<P>
"If MFN had not been renewed, China surely would have
retaliated against U.S. exports, placing this thriving market in
jeopardy, helping our competitors," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
